{"title_page": "Center for Automotive Research", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Underlinked|date=June 2013}}\n{{Refimprove|date=March 2019}}}}\nThe '''Center for Automotive Research''' ('''CAR''') is a [[Nonprofit organization|nonprofit]] research organization based in [[Ann Arbor, Michigan]] that conducts research, forecasts trends, develops new [[Methodology|methodologies]], and advises on [[public policy]].\n\n==History==\n===Office for the Study of Automotive Transportation===\nBefore its current status as an independent nonprofit research organization, CAR was part of the [[University of Michigan]], under the name \"'''Office for the Study of Automotive Transportation'''\" which was a unit of the University of Michigan [[Transportation Research Institute]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://quod.lib.umich.edu/cgi/f/findaid/findaid-idx?c=bhlead;idno=umich-bhl-89504;view=reslist;didno=umich-bhl-89504;subview=standard;focusrgn=summaryinfo;cc=bhlead|title=Office for the Study of Automotive Transportation (University of Michigan) records|first=University of Michigan Office for the Study of Automotive|last=Transportation|website=Quod.lib.umich.edu|accessdate=26 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{POV section|date=December 2013}}\n===Center for Automotive Research===\nIn 2003, the Center for Automotive Research (CAR) was established as an independent non-profit research organization. CAR creates [[economic]] and [[systems modeling]] research, develops new manufacturing methodologies, forecasts industry futures, advises on public policy, and conducts industry conferences and forums. As an example of its economic research, CAR chairman [[emeritus]] [[David Cole]] has in relation to the [[Tesla US dealership disputes#Michigan|Tesla Michigan dealership dispute]] said: \"The value of [[Tesla, Inc.|Tesla]] is all based on hype and not substance\".<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.detroitnews.com/story/business/autos/2017/08/08/tesla-fighting-michigan-sales-law/104423752/ |website= [[Detroitnews.com]] |title= Tesla fighting Michigan sales law as Model 3 rolls out |first= Jonathan |last= Oosting |date= 2017-08-08 |accessdate= 2017-08-09}}</ref>\n\n===Research Groups===\nCAR research is divided into three distinct research groups: Industry, Labor & Economics; Manufacturing, Engineering & Technology; and Transportation Systems Analysis.\n\n====Industry, Labor, & Economics====\nThe Industry, Labor, & Economics Group researches the intersection of the [[automotive industry]], [[technology]], [[Economy|economy,]] [[society]], and [[Public policy|public policy,]] and is home to CAR\u2019s Automotive Communities Partnership. Their research encompasses a wide spectrum of automotive analysis, from employment, talent, skills, and labor issues to automotive trade, global competitiveness, and development in [[North America]] and in emerging economies, to [[Quantify|quantifying]] the industry\u2019s economic contribution and industry trends. The group\u2019s research areas include [[Automotive industry|automotive]] business, markets, economic contributions, investments, plants, products, people, and communities.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\n====Manufacturing, Engineering & Technology====\nThe Manufacturing, Engineering & Technology Group focuses on evolving technologies and manufacturing engineering systems, primarily in the automotive industry. Technology and product planning are combined with manufacturing to provide a comprehensive and strategic perspective. A significant effort continues to support improving the performance of [[vehicle]] development through research in manufacturing systems, tooling, and new technologies of car and light-truck bodies. Research is directed at reducing new vehicle development costs and lead time while improving product quality. Recent efforts have been aimed at technology assessment to support improved [[fuel economy]] through advanced [[Powertrain|powertrains]] and vehicle mass reduction. This group oversees several industry-led [[Coalition|coalitions]] involving the automotive, utility, tooling, and materials industries.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\n====Transportation Systems Analysis====\nThe Transportation Systems Analysis group is concerned with the broad context within which [[Motor vehicle|motor vehicles]] are operated. Much of this effort focuses on the planning and operation of [[transportation infrastructure]], as well as on interactions between [[infrastructure]], [[Vehicle|vehicles]], and vehicle operators. Increasingly, this research includes [[Information and communications technology|communications technology]] as a key component of these interactions. In this area, the group is heavily involved in connected vehicle and intelligent transportation systems work. Ultimately, the goals of these efforts are to help both the [[Automotive industry|automotive]] and [[Transport|transportation]] industries deploy technologies that enhance safety, improve [[mobility]], contribute to economic vitality, and reduce the environmental consequences of transportation.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\n==Events==\n===Breakfast Briefing Series===\nThe CAR Breakfast Briefings are an educational series, smaller than the flagship [http://www.cargroup.org/mbs Management Briefing Seminars], with the same intent of educating industry participants, media and the general public, on a wide variety of emerging industry topics.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|1=https://www.cargroup.org/}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Automotive industry in the United States]]\n[[Category:Research organizations in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Underlinked|date=June 2013}}\n{{Refimprove|date=March 2019}}}}\nThe '''Center for Automotive Research''' ('''CAR''') is a [[Nonprofit organization|nonprofit]] research organization based in [[Ann Arbor, Michigan]] that conducts research, forecasts trends, develops new methodologies, and advises on [[public policy]].\n\n==History==\n===Office for the Study of Automotive Transportation===\nBefore its current status as an independent nonprofit research organization, CAR was part of the [[University of Michigan]], under the name \"'''Office for the Study of Automotive Transportation'''\" which was a unit of the University of Michigan [[Transportation Research Institute]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://quod.lib.umich.edu/cgi/f/findaid/findaid-idx?c=bhlead;idno=umich-bhl-89504;view=reslist;didno=umich-bhl-89504;subview=standard;focusrgn=summaryinfo;cc=bhlead|title=Office for the Study of Automotive Transportation (University of Michigan) records|first=University of Michigan Office for the Study of Automotive|last=Transportation|website=Quod.lib.umich.edu|accessdate=26 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{POV section|date=December 2013}}\n===Center for Automotive Research===\nIn 2003, the Center for Automotive Research (CAR) was established as an independent non-profit research organization. CAR creates [[economic]] and [[systems modeling]] research, develops new manufacturing methodologies, forecasts industry futures, advises on public policy, and conducts industry conferences and forums. As an example of its economic research, CAR chairman emeritus [[David Cole]] has in relation to the [[Tesla US dealership disputes#Michigan|Tesla Michigan dealership dispute]] said: \"The value of [[Tesla, Inc.|Tesla]] is all based on hype and not substance\".<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.detroitnews.com/story/business/autos/2017/08/08/tesla-fighting-michigan-sales-law/104423752/ |website= [[Detroitnews.com]] |title= Tesla fighting Michigan sales law as Model 3 rolls out |first= Jonathan |last= Oosting |date= 2017-08-08 |accessdate= 2017-08-09}}</ref>\n\n===Research Groups===\nCAR research is divided into three distinct research groups: Industry, Labor & Economics; Manufacturing, Engineering & Technology; and Transportation Systems Analysis.\n\n====Industry, Labor, & Economics====\nThe Industry, Labor, & Economics Group researches the intersection of the [[automotive industry]], [[technology]], [[Economy|economy,]] [[society]], and [[Public policy|public policy,]] and is home to CAR\u2019s Automotive Communities Partnership. Their research encompasses a wide spectrum of automotive analysis, from employment, talent, skills, and labor issues to automotive trade, global competitiveness, and development in [[North America]] and in emerging economies, to [[Quantify|quantifying]] the industry\u2019s economic contribution and industry trends. The group\u2019s research areas include [[Automotive industry|automotive]] business, markets, economic contributions, investments, plants, products, people, and communities.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\n====Manufacturing, Engineering & Technology====\nThe Manufacturing, Engineering & Technology Group focuses on evolving technologies and manufacturing engineering systems, primarily in the automotive industry. Technology and product planning are combined with manufacturing to provide a comprehensive and strategic perspective. A significant effort continues to support improving the performance of [[vehicle]] development through research in manufacturing systems, tooling, and new technologies of car and light-truck bodies. Research is directed at reducing new vehicle development costs and lead time while improving product quality. Recent efforts have been aimed at technology assessment to support improved [[fuel economy]] through advanced [[Powertrain|powertrains]] and vehicle mass reduction. This group oversees several industry-led coalitions involving the automotive, utility, tooling, and materials industries.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\n====Transportation Systems Analysis====\nThe Transportation Systems Analysis group is concerned with the broad context within which [[Motor vehicle|motor vehicles]] are operated. Much of this effort focuses on the planning and operation of [[transportation infrastructure]], as well as on interactions between [[infrastructure]], [[Vehicle|vehicles]], and vehicle operators. Increasingly, this research includes [[Information and communications technology|communications technology]] as a key component of these interactions. In this area, the group is heavily involved in connected vehicle and intelligent transportation systems work. Ultimately, the goals of these efforts are to help both the [[Automotive industry|automotive]] and [[Transport|transportation]] industries deploy technologies that enhance safety, improve [[mobility]], contribute to economic vitality, and reduce the environmental consequences of transportation.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\n==Events==\n===Breakfast Briefing Series===\nThe CAR Breakfast Briefings are an educational series, smaller than the flagship [http://www.cargroup.org/mbs Management Briefing Seminars], with the same intent of educating industry participants, media and the general public, on a wide variety of emerging industry topics.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|1=https://www.cargroup.org/}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Automotive industry in the United States]]\n[[Category:Research organizations in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Alessiu1998", "label": "safe", "comment": "Wikilinks", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Center_for_Automotive_Research"}
{"title_page": "Ae Dil Hai Mushkil", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Infobox film\n| image          = Ae Dil Hai Mushkil.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Karan Johar]]\n| producer       = Hiroo Yash Johar<br>[[Karan Johar]]<br>Apoorva Mehta\n| writer         = '''Story & Screenplay:'''<br>[[Karan Johar]]<br />'''Dialogues:'''<br>[[Karan Johar]]<br />[[Niranjan Iyengar]]\n| starring       = [[Ranbir Kapoor]]<br />[[Anushka Sharma]]<br />[[Aishwarya Rai Bachchan]]\n| music          = [[Pritam]]\n| cinematography = [[Anil Mehta]]\n| editing        = Manik Dawar\n| studio         = [[Dharma Productions]]\n| distributor    = [[Fox Star Studios]]\n| released       = {{Film date|df=y|2016|10|28}}\n| runtime        = 157 minutes\n| country        = [[India]]\n| language       = Hindi\n| budget         = {{INR}}59 crore<ref>{{cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/photos/entertainment-gallery/ae-dil-hai-mushkil-vs-shivaay-who-will-win-at-the-box-office/4/|title=Ae Dil Hai Mushkil vs Shivaay: Who will win at the box office?|newspaper=The Indian Express}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.firstpost.com/bollywood/ae-dil-hai-mushkil-shivaay-have-close-contest-at-box-office-kjos-film-has-a-10-cr-lead-3088338.html|title=Ae Dil Hai Mushkil, Shivaay have close contest at box office; KJo's film has a 10-cr lead|work=Firstpost|accessdate=4 November 2016}}</ref>\n| gross          = {{Estimation}} {{INR}}223.51 crore<ref name=\"grossfilm\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/box-office-special-features/box-office-worldwide-collections-day-wise-breakup-ae-dil-hai-mushkil/|title=Box Office: Worldwide Collection and Day Wise Breakup of Ae Dil Hai Mushkil|work=[[Bollywood Hungama]]|accessdate=21 November 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Ae Dil Hai Mushkil''''' is an [[India|Indian]] [[List of Bollywood films of 2016|2016]] [[Hindi language]] [[Musical film|musical]] [[romantic drama film]] directed, produced and written by [[Karan Johar]]. The music is composed by [[Pritam]] with screenplay by Johar.<ref name=\"adhm\">{{cite news|last=Leydon |first=Joe |title=Film Review: \u2018Ae Dil Hai Mushkil\u2019 |url=https://variety.com/2016/film/reviews/ae-dil-hai-mushkil-review-1201903527/ |work=Variety |date=28 October 2016 |accessdate=14 January 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161029110812/http://variety.com/2016/film/reviews/ae-dil-hai-mushkil-review-1201903527/ |archivedate=29 October 2016 }}</ref> It stars [[Ranbir Kapoor]], [[Anushka Sharma]] and [[Aishwarya Rai]] with special appearances by [[Shah Rukh Khan]] and [[Alia Bhatt]] and was released worldwide on 28 October 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/photos/entertainment-gallery/ae-dil-hai-mushkil-vs-shivaay-who-will-win-at-the-box-office/4/|title=Ae Dil Hai Mushkil vs Shivaay: Who will win at the box office?|newspaper=The Indian Express}}</ref>\n\nThe film opened with positive response and was particularly praised for its soundtrack, that won four [[Filmfare Awards]] in January 2017. It went on to gross {{INRConvert|2.23|b}} worldwide, becoming a critical and commercial success.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.firstpost.com/bollywood/ae-dil-hai-mushkil-shivaay-have-close-contest-at-box-office-kjos-film-has-a-10-cr-lead-3088338.html|title=Ae Dil Hai Mushkil, Shivaay have close contest at box office; KJo's film has a 10-cr lead|work=Firstpost|accessdate=4 November 2016}}</ref> The film was declared a hit at box office.<ref name=\"grossfilm\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/box-office-special-features/box-office-worldwide-collections-day-wise-breakup-ae-dil-hai-mushkil/|title=Box Office: Worldwide Collection and Day Wise Breakup of Ae Dil Hai Mushkil|work=[[Bollywood Hungama]]|accessdate=21 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Plot ==\nThe film begins with the interview of Ayan Sanger ([[Ranbir Kapoor]]), a singer who has newly acquired fame with his non-filmy songs. He tells the story of his experience of love in a flashback. A few years ago, in [[London]], a chance meeting in a disco between Ayan, the son of a millionaire, a novice in terms of sex-related matters, and Alizeh Khan ([[Anushka Sharma]]), who knows about sex a little more, ends up with them trying to make out, and it turning into a comedy. They get to know about each other and become friends. Later, when they discover their respective partners are cheating on them, they break up with their lovers: Ayan with Lisa D'Souza and Alizeh with \"Dr.\" Faisal Khan and the two go to Paris to spend a week together. While Ayan falls in love with Alizeh but does not tell her while she considers him to be only a \"friend\". One day, Alizeh stumbles upon DJ Ali, her ex-boyfriend/lover, who wants to reconcile. Partially confused, but still in love with him, Alizeh decides to go with DJ Ali, and so unintentionally stops hanging out with Ayan and they cease communication.\n\nA few days later, Alizeh calls and invites Ayan to her wedding with DJ Ali in [[Lucknow]]. Ayan is petrified on hearing this but agrees to the invitation. At the wedding, he tells Alizeh he loves her but she rejects his feelings causing Ayan to leave the ceremony heartbroken. At the airport to board a flight to [[Dubai]], he meets Saba Taliyar Khan ([[Aishwarya Rai Bachchan]]), a poet, who is leaving for [[Vienna]]. She consoles Ayan and gives him a book with her poetry and number on it. Ayan calls after three months stating that he is in Vienna and wants to meet her. He learns that Saba is divorced and has no place for love in her heart. Later, he also meets Saba's ex-husband, Tahir Taliyar Khan ([[Shah Rukh Khan]]) in a fine arts gallery, who tells him that one-sided love is not a weakness but empowering. Ayan, who had blocked Alizeh from contacting him in all ways, finally calls and reconnects with her. He begins to send pictures of Saba to her to try and induce jealousy.\n\nOne day Alizeh informs Ayan that she's coming to Vienna and wants to meet him. Ayan invites her for dinner with Saba to provoke Alizeh into loving him, but Alizeh thinks Ayan has found love in Saba and is happy for him. Meanwhile, Saba begins to develop feelings for Ayan, but he loves Alizeh. Seeing his love for Alizeh, Saba asks him to leave.\n\nAyan continues to harbor love for Alizeh and becomes a famous singer with his channel. He meets Ali one day and realizes that Ali and Alizeh  have parted ways. Ayan goes to Alizeh's favorite spot and waits there until she arrives. Alizeh tells Ayan that she is diagnosed with cancer stage IV and will not live much longer. Ayan and Alizeh try to make the best of their time together. Ayan tries to make Alizeh love him, to no avail. This leads to a fight between the two, and Alizeh decides to leave Ayan. Next morning Ayan tries to search for Alizeh, apparently reaching the airport and thus fulfilling her last wish also before death. Eventually, Ayan makes peace with the fact that he and Alizeh can at least be friends and nothing more. Alizeh dies soon. The screen blacks out and comes back to the present where Ayan, still a popular singer, is giving an interview based on the love of his life. Ayan sings the song ''\"[[Channa Mereya]]\"'', which is inspired by his one-sided love story, and finishes the interview.\n\n== Cast ==\n===Main cast===\n* [[Ranbir Kapoor]] as Ayan Sanger\n* [[Anushka Sharma]] as Alizeh Khan\n* [[Aishwarya Rai Bachchan]] as Saba Taliyar Khan\n*[[Fawad Khan]] as DJ Ali\n\n===Cameo appearances===\n*[[Shah Rukh Khan]] as Tahir Taliyar Khan, Saba's ex-husband\n* [[Imran Abbas]] as Dr. Faisal Khan, Alizeh's boyfriend\n* [[Lisa Haydon]] as Lisa D'Souza, Ayan's girlfriend\n* [[Alia Bhatt]] as Nisha (Alizeh's DJ friend) in the song \"The Breakup Song\"\n*[[Neha Dhupia]] as the reporter (voiceover)\n\n== Production ==\n\n=== Development ===\n{{Quote box\n |quote=\"...it is not a conventional love story or love triangle. It's a film that dwells deeply on relationships, heartbreaks and how love completes you, defines you and yet leaves you wanting for more. I have never had, in my entire career, a film that has come to me so fast, so organically and so from within.\"\n |source = \u2014[[Karan Johar]] speaking about the film in an interview with ''[[The Times of India]]''<ref name=\"toi\" />\n |align = right\n |width = 33%\n}}\nThe film was first announced in November 2014. Writer-director [[Karan Johar]] said that for the past year and a half, he had been developing a story that he needed to work on for several months. However, while he was in New York, the idea for ''Ae Dil Hai Mushkil'' (Title taken from a song of 1956 film ''[[C.I.D. (1956 film)|C.I.D.]]'') came to him and he wrote the screenplay in 30 days. When he came back to India, he spoke to the three lead actors and they all signed on immediately. Johar stated that he was motivated to cast [[Ranbir Kapoor]] and [[Anushka Sharma]] in the film after getting to know them by acting with them in [[Anurag Kashyap]]'s ''[[Bombay Velvet]]'' (2015). He added that he was excited to cast [[Aishwarya Rai Bachchan]] after several unsuccessful attempts to cast her in his previous films like ''[[Kuch Kuch Hota Hai]]'' (1998), ''[[Kabhi Khushi Kabhie Gham...]]'' (2001), and ''[[Kabhi Alvida Naa Kehna]]'' (2006).<ref name=\"toi\">{{cite news|last=Gupta|first=Priya|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Karan-Johar-to-direct-Aishwarya-Ranbir-and-Anushka-in-Ae-Dil-Hai-Mushkil/articleshow/45325296.cms|work=The Times of India|title=Karan Johar to direct Aishwarya, Ranbir, and Anushka in 'Ae Dil Hai Mushkil'|date=1 December 2014|accessdate=13 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nActor [[Fawad Khan]] was cast to play a role of a DJ, describing his role as \"not exactly a cameo but it becomes a backbone for a certain conflict of a character in the movie.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/role-in-ae-dil-hai-mushkil-not-exactly-cameo-fawad-khan/|title=Role in 'Ae Dil Hai Mushkil' not exactly a cameo: Fawad Khan|work=The Indian Express|date=9 March 2016|accessdate=27 July 2016}}</ref> [[Lisa Haydon]] has also confirmed that she will appear in the film.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report-had-fun-filming-ae-dil-hai-mushkil-lisa-haydon-2230328 |title= Had fun filming 'Ae Dil Hai Mushkil': Lisa Haydon |work= DNA India |date=2 July 2016 |accessdate= 27 July 2016}}</ref> In September 2016 at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]], Johar confirmed that [[Shah Rukh Khan]] had also filmed a scene for the movie.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/ae-dil-hai-mushkil-shah-rukh-khan-karan-johar-3026728/|title=Ae Dil Hai Mushkil: Karan Johar confirms Shah Rukh Khan cameo in film|work=The Indian Express|date=12 September 2016|accessdate=13 September 2016}}</ref> In October 2016, he confirmed that [[Alia Bhatt]] would also make a cameo appearance in the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/alia-bhatt-has-a-cameo-in-ae-dil-hai-mushkil-she-stars-as-1474855|title=Alia Bhatt Has a Cameo in Ae Dil Hai Mushkil. She Stars As...|publisher=NDTV|accessdate=16 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 February at the India Conference at Harvard, Johar revealed that in the film Ranbir Kapoor plays the character of a Hindu boy named ''Ayan'' and Anushka Sharma plays a Muslim girl named ''Alizeh''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-hollywood-stars-won-t-have-much-to-do-in-our-cinema-karan-johar-2174971|title=Hollywood stars won't have much to do in our cinema: Karan Johar|work=Daily News and Analysis|date=7 February 2016|accessdate=7 February 2016}}</ref> The two leading female characters were originally supposed to be Pakistani women in the movie. However, Karan Johar decided to change the female characters to Indian Muslims to avoid further trouble after the film ran into controversy over the casting of Fawad Khan, a Pakistani national.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report-characters-changed-aishwarya-and-anushka-won-t-play-pakistanis-in-ae-dil-hai-mushkil-anymore-2262152|title=Characters changed? Aishwarya and Anushka won't play Pakistanis in 'Ae Dil Hai Mushkil' anymore!|work=DNA India|date=7 October 2016|accessdate=7 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Filming ===\nPrincipal photography began in September 2015 with Kapoor and Sharma in [[London]]. At the end of September, the team filmed some portions in [[Paris]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Goswami|first=Parismita|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/after-london-ranbir-kapoor-anushka-sharma-fly-paris-ae-dil-hai-mushkil-shoot-photo-648607|work=International Business Times|title=After London, Ranbir Kapoor, Anushka Sharma fly to Paris for 'Ae Dil Hai Mushkil' shoot|date=30 September 2015|accessdate=13 October 2015}}</ref> In October, they began shooting in various locations in [[Austria]], including the city of [[Vienna]]. Aishwarya Rai Bachchan joined the crew in Vienna in mid-October after the release of her film ''[[Jazbaa]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/after-london-ranbir-kapoor-anushka-sharmas-ae-dil-hai-mushkil-in-paris-austria/|work=The Indian Express|title=After London, Ranbir Kapoor, Anushka Sharma's 'Ae Dil Hai Mushkil' in Paris, Austria|date=7 October 2015|accessdate=13 October 2015}}</ref> In March 2016, Kapoor, Sharma, and Khan were seen filming in [[Mandawa]], [[Rajasthan]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/entertainment/bollywood/270316/ranbir-anushka-and-fawad-kick-start-ae-dil-hai-mushkil-shoot-in-rajasthan.html|title=Ranbir, Anushka and Fawad kick start Ae Dil Hai Mushkil shoot in Rajasthan|work=[[Deccan Chronicle]]|accessdate=27 March 2016}}</ref> In July 2016, Johar tweeted a photo of Kapoor and Sharma on set in [[Mumbai]] for the last schedule.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Karan-Johar-begins-shooting-last-leg-of-Ae-Dil-Hai-Mushkil/articleshow/53250813.cms|title=Karan Johar begins shooting last leg of 'Ae Dil Hai Mushkil'|work=The Times of India|date=17 July 2016|accessdate=27 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Release ==\n\n=== Screening issue ===\nOn 8 October 2016, Indian political party, [[Maharashtra Navnirman Sena]] (MNS), proclaimed that they would not allow the release of the film, following nationwide protests surrounding the [[2016 Uri attack|terrorist attack in Jammu and Kashmir]] on 18 September 2016 and the decision by Cinema Owners Exhibitors Association of India preventing the release of films with [[Pakistani]] actors in four states \u2013 Maharashtra, Gujarat, Karnataka, and Goa. Citing the casting of Pakistani actor [[Fawad Khan]] in the film, the MNS warned theater owners around the country to not screen the film, threatening them with vandalism. Announcing that security will be tightened at theaters along with sufficient police protection, Maharashtra chief minister, [[Devendra Fadnavis]], commented on the issue, saying, \"Anyone found taking the law into their hands will be dealt with firmly.\" He also informed that 12 MNS members were sent to judicial custody after they barged into a Mumbai theater and held a protest on 19 October 2016.<ref>[http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/mumbai/Cops-set-up-helpline-for-movie-theatres-as-MNS-threat-looms/articleshow/54948796.cms MNS: Ae Dil Hai Mushkil: Cops set up helpline for movie theatres as MNS threat looms \u2013 Times of India]. Timesofindia.indiatimes.com (20 October 2016). Retrieved on 2016-11-01.</ref>\n\nCommenting on the ruckus behind his film's release, director Karan Johar said that the circumstances in which the film was shot in 2015 were completely different. \"Going forward, I would like to say that of course, I will not engage with talent from the neighbouring country, given the circumstance. But with that same energy, I beseech you to know one thing \u2013 that over 300 people in my Indian crew have put their blood, sweat, and tears into making my film, ''Ae Dil Hai Mushkil''. I don't think it's fair for them to face any kind of turbulence on account of other fellow Indians,\" he further added in a video statement. He was heavily criticized by news and social media for buckling under pressure.<ref>[http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/ae-dil-hai-mushkil-islamaphobia-mns-karan-johar/1/790876.html Fresh threat to Ae Dil Hai Mushkil from MNS : India, News \u2013 India Today]. Indiatoday.intoday.in (19 October 2016). Retrieved on 2016-11-01.</ref> However, people from the film fraternity like [[Mukesh Bhatt]] and [[Shyam Benegal]] supported Johar and his film, and requested the people to consider the film and its release without giving importance to the actors' nationalities.\n\nOn 20 October 2016, Mukesh Bhatt said that his discussion with Union home minister, [[Rajnath Singh]], had been consequential, and affirmed that the film will be screened throughout the country without any violence. However, he promised that he would not make any more films with Pakistani actors.<ref>[http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/magazines/panache/karan-johar-film-guild-to-meet-rajnath-singh-to-discussrelease-of-ae-dil-hai-mushkil/articleshow/54953596.cms 'Ae Dil Hai Mushkil' will have a safe Diwali release: Mukesh Bhatt after meeting Rajnath Singh \u2013 The Economic Times]. Economictimes.indiatimes.com (20 October 2016). Retrieved on 2016-11-01.</ref>\n\n== Box office ==\n''Ae Dil Hai Mushkil'' was made on a total budget of over {{INR}}100 crore ($15 million), including marketing and distribution costs. Prior to its release, the film had already recouped {{INR}}75 crore ($11.2 million) from music, satellite and digital rights, so it needed to recover only {{INR}}25 crore ($3.7 million) from the domestic box office. Worldwide, the film earned \u20b990.84 crore ($13.6 million) on its opening weekend,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koimoi.com/box-office/ae-dil-hai-mushkil-grosses-over-90-crores-worldwide-in-its-opening-weekend/|title=Ae Dil Hai Mushkil Grosses Over 115 Crores Worldwide In Its Opening Weekend|author=Koimoi.com Team|work=[[Koimoi.com]]|date=31 October 2016|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> while [[ComScore]] reported an estimated $12.8 million from 14 markets.<ref name=\"Overseas46thOpening\" /> As of November, it has made $21.3 million worldwide.<ref name=\"Overseas50thOpening\">{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2016/11/doctor-strange-marvel-trolls-china-benedict-cumberbatch-overseas-results-international-box-office-weekend-1201849687/|title=\u2018Doctor Strange\u2019 Supreme With $240M+ Overseas/$325M+ Global; \u2018Bridget Jones\u2019 Delivers $200M+ WW \u2013 Intl Box Office|author=Nancy Tartaglione|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=6 November 2016|accessdate=7 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn India, its domestic market, the film had to compete with ''[[Shivaay]]'' which was released on the same day during the lucrative [[Diwali]] weekend.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/dongroves/2016/10/25/bollywood-showdown-ajay-devgns-shivaay-vs-karan-johars-ae-dil-hai-mushkil/#70fbdee97db3|title=Bollywood Showdown: Ajay Devgn's 'Shivaay' Vs Karan Johar's 'Ae Dil Hai Mushkil'|author=Don Groves|work=[[Forbes]]|date=25 October 2016|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> On its opening day the film made {{INR}}13.30 crore, the third biggest for both Kapoor and Sharma,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koimoi.com/box-office/ranbir-anushka-register-their-3rd-biggest-opening-ever-with-ae-dil-hai-mushkil/|title=Ranbir & Anushka Register Their 3rd Biggest Opening Ever With Ae Dil Hai Mushkil|author=Joginder Tuteja|work=[[Koimoi.com]]|date=29 October 2016|accessdate=2 November 2016}}</ref> and the sixth biggest for a Bollywood film of the year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/box-office-special-features/box-office-ae-dil-hai-mushkil-becomes-2nd-highest-opening-weekend-grosser-2016-overseas/|title=Box Office: Ae Dil Hai Mushkil becomes 2nd Highest opening weekend grosser of 2016 in the overseas|work=[[Bollywood Hungama]]|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> Through its opening weekend, it scored a debut of {{INR}}35.60 crore ($5.3 million) net in its three days on 3,200 screens, equating to a gross {{INR}}49.84 crore ($7.65 million), the ninth-biggest debut of the year<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koimoi.com/box-office/highest-weekend/2016-films/|title=Top 10 Highest Opening Weekend Grossers Of 2016|date=31 October 2016|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> and the best ever debut for Johar, beating ''[[My Name is Khan]]''{{'}}s \u20b931.50 crore ($4.7 million).<ref name=\"Forbes\">{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/dongroves/2016/10/30/karan-johar-vs-ajay-devgn-surprising-result-in-bollywood-showdown/#1e8e45687e07|title=Karan Johar Vs Ajay Devgn: Surprising Result In Bollywood Showdown|author=Don Groves|work=[[Forbes]]|date=30 October 2016|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> On Monday, it saw a hike in ticket sales, earning {{INR}}17.75 crore ($2.65 million) due to the holiday season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/ae-dil-hai-mushkil-box-office-collection-day-5-this-is-the-hit-ranbir-kapoor-needed-3732593/|title=Ae Dil Hai Mushkil box office collection day 5: This is the hit Ranbir Kapoor needed|work=[[The Indian Express]]|date=1 November 2016|accessdate=2 November 2016}}</ref> In its first full week, the film earned \u20b980.19 crore ($12 million) in India alone and $20.2 million worldwide.<ref name=\"6million\">{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/dongroves/2016/11/03/karan-johar-and-ajay-devgn-set-to-continue-their-hot-streaks-in-india/#238d4a9af0b3|title=Karan Johar And Ajay Devgn Set To Continue Their Hot Streaks In India|author=Don Groves|work=[[Forbes]]|date=3 November 2016|accessdate=5 November 2016}}</ref> The film continued to dominate the box office in its second weekend, earning $3.2 million from 2,000 screens (\u22121,200 screens).<ref name=\"ForbesS\">{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/dongroves/2016/11/06/karan-johar-ajay-devgn-ranbir-kapoor-anushka-sharma-and-aishwarya-reach-new-peaks/#42bb032a6f59|title=Karan Johar, Ajay Devgn, Ranbir Kapoor, Anushka Sharma And Aishwarya Reach New Peaks|author=Scott Mendelson|work=[[Forbes]]|date=6 November 2016|accessdate=7 November 2016}}</ref> In just 10 days, the film earned {{INR}}97.17 crore ($14.6 million) net and has become the sixth highest-grossing Bollywood film in the country. Moreover, the film now ranks as the highest-earner for Aishwarya, beating ''[[Dhoom 2]]''{{'}}s {{INR}}82.30 crore ($12.3 million) in 2006; the fourth biggest for Anushka as well as for Ranbir.<ref name=\"ForbesS\" />\n\nIn the United Kingdom, it recorded the biggest Bollywood opening of the year with \u20b94.88 crore ($772,891), debuting at eighth place at the U.K. box office.<ref name=\"Overseas46thOpening\">{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2016/10/doctor-strange-overseas-opening-benedict-cumberbatch-marvel-inferno-trolls-china-international-box-office-weekend-results-1201844444/|title=\u2018Doctor Strange\u2019 Brews $86M In Overseas Bow; Tops Comps, Sets IMAX Records \u2013 International Box Office Update|author=Nancy Tartaglione|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=30 October 2016|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> However, this is inclusive of previews. Including previews, ''[[Sultan (2016 film)|Sultan]]'' would be the clear winner with a $1.3 million debut in July. But excluding previews, ''Ae Dil Hai Mushkil'' is ahead of the former.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/filmblog/2016/nov/01/uk-box-office-doctor-strange-film-benedict-cumberbatch-i-daniel-blake|title=Doctor Strange sweeps into a new cosmic realm at UK box office|author=Charles Gant|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=1 November 2016|accessdate=6 November 2016}}</ref> In the United States and Canada, the film received a [[limited release]] across 302 theaters and grossed {{INR}}14 crore ($2.13 million) in its opening weekend finishing in tenth place.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2016/10/moonlight-gimme-danger-oasis-weekend-specialty-box-office-1201845224/|title=\u2018Moonlight\u2019 Shines With Over $900K in 36 Theaters; Magnolia's \u2018Gimme Danger\u2019 Solid in Debut \u2013 Specialty Box Office|author=Brian Brooks|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=30 October 2016|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nBy the end of its theatrical run, the film grossed {{INR}}146.64 crore in India and {{INR}}223.51 crore worldwide.<ref name=\"grossfilm\" />\n\n== Critical reception ==\n[[Rotten Tomatoes]] gives the film a 50% score based on 14 critic reviews, with an average rating of 5.4/10.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/ae_dil_hai_mushkil |title=Ae Dil Hai Mushkil |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |access-date=7 December 2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], which assigns a normalized rating, the film has a score of 40 out of 100, based on four critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/ae-dil-hai-mushkil|title=Ae Dil Hai Mushkil Reviews|website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=19 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n''[[Bollywood Hungama]]'' gave 4/5 ratings and commented, \"a contemporary and a progressive take on relationships from the master story teller Karan Johar\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/ae-dil-hai-mushkil/critic-review/|title=Movie Review: Ae Dil Hai Mushkil|work=[[Bollywood Hungama]]|date=28 October 2016|accessdate=5 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nRaja Sen and Sukanya Verma of ''[[Rediff.com]]'' respectively rated 4/5 and 3.5/5 and said, \"Thank you, Karan Johar for this film feels like a sob. Johar has improved massively as a storyteller, this film is more polished and assured than anything he's done before.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/report/review-ae-dil-hai-mushkil-is-an-intense-story-of-love/20161028.htm|title=Review: Ae Dil Hai Mushkil is an intense story of love|publisher=Raja Sen|work=[[Rediff.com]]|date=28 October 2016|accessdate=5 December 2016}}</ref> and, \"As evident by his body of work, Karan Johar has a sweet spot for this attribute, in the splendidly romantic and richly satisfying ''ADHM''.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Ae Dil Hai Mushkil Review: Splendidly romantic and richly satisfying\n|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/report/ae-dil-hai-mushkil-review-splendidly-romantic-richly-satisfying/20161028.htm|publisher=Sukanya Verma|work=Rediff.com|date=28 October 2016|accessdate=5 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nNihit Bhave of ''[[The Times of India]]'' rated 3.5/5 and said, \"a beautiful-looking film that isn't bereft of logic\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.com/entertainment/hindi/movie-reviews/Ae-Dil-Hai-Mushkil/movie-review/55112044.cms|title=Ae Dil Hai Mushkil Movie Review|newspaper=[[The Times of India]]|publisher=Nihit Bhave|date=28 October 2016|accessdate=5 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[Subhash K. Jha]] of ''[[Deccan Chronicle]]'' rated 2.5/5 and said, \"''ADHM'' is one good looking film with actors who epitomise human beauty.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/entertainment/movie-reviews/281016/ae-dil-hai-mushkil-movie-review-a-flawed-nugget-like-life-itself.html|title=Ae Dil Hai Mushkil movie review: A flawed nugget, like life itself|newspaper=[[Deccan Chronicle]]|publisher=Subhash K Jha|date=28 October 2016|accessdate=5 December 2016}}</ref> Sweta Kaushal of ''[[Hindustan Times]]'' rated 2.5/5, saying \"''ADHM'' offers little in terms of story and fails to get the audience empathise or feel for the characters and events in the movie.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hindustantimes.com/movie-reviews/ae-dil-hai-mushkil-despite-an-awesome-ranbir-anushka-chemistry-it-is-difficult-to-feel-for-this-one/story-uDYlouZKZD9MT7UvPecM8I.html|title=Ae Dil Hai Mushkil review: This Ranbir-Anushka film is hard to relate to|date=29 October 2016|publisher=Sweta Kaushal|newspaper=[[Hindustan Times]]|accessdate=5 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nShubhra Gupta of ''[[The Indian Express]]'' rated 2/5 and said, \"Johar is unable to go the extra mile, hope that Johar will come up with something newer and sharper the next time around.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/movie-review/ae-dil-hai-mushkil-movie-review-adhm-karan-johar-ranbir-kapoor-anushka-sharma-star-rating-3727068/|title=Ae Dil Hai Mushkil movie review: Karan Johar needs to deliver a newer, sharper film|publisher=Shubhra Gupta|newspaper=[[The Indian Express]]|date=29 October 2016|accessdate=5 December 2016}}</ref> Mike McCahill of ''[[The Guardian]]'' rated 2/5 and said, \"Despite controversy over the casting, Karan Johar's romance, has a failure of nerve about Hindu-Muslim relations.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2016/oct/28/ae-dil-hai-mushkil-review-karan-johar-fawad-khan|title=Ae Dil Hai Mushkil review&nbsp;\u2013 a traditional weepie, unlikely to offend|date=28 October 2016|publisher=Mike McCahill|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=5 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n''[[The Hindu]]'' commented, \"''ADHM'' is the latest in the brand of cinema that isn't so much as plot driven as it is focused on characters, relationships, and interactions.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/cinema-reviews/Ae-Dil-Hai-Mushkil-Sluggish-narrative-overtakes-a-fresh-film/article16085359.ece?secname=entertainment&secpage=true|title=Ae Dil Hai Mushkil: Sluggish narrative overtakes a fresh film|date=28 October 2016|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|accessdate=5 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nReuters commented, \"''ADHM'' has neither gravitas nor the charm to be worth remembering.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/1224231/movie-review-ae-dil-hai-mushkil/|title=Movie Review: Ae Dil Hai Mushkil|newspaper=[[The Express Tribune]]|publisher=Reuters|date=8 November 2016|accessdate=5 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Soundtrack ==\n{{Main|Ae Dil Hai Mushkil (soundtrack)}}\n\n== Accolades ==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Award\n! scope=\"col\" | Date of Ceremony\n! scope=\"col\" | Category\n! scope=\"col\" | Recipient(s) and nominee(s)\n! scope=\"col\" | Result\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | {{Abbr|Ref(s)|Reference(s)}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"8\" scope=\"row\" | [[Filmfare Awards]]\n| rowspan=\"8\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[62nd Filmfare Awards|14 January 2017]]\n| [[Filmfare Award for Best Director|Best Director]]\n| {{sort|Johar|[[Karan Johar]]}}\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"8\" style=\"text-align:center;\" |<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmfare.com/awards/filmfare-awards-2017/nominations|title=Filmfare Awards 2017 Nominations|date=15 January 2017|accessdate=15 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmfare.com/awards/filmfare-awards-2017/winners|title=Filmfare Awards 2017 Winners|date=15 January 2017|accessdate=15 January 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Filmfare Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]]\n| {{sort|Kapoor|[[Ranbir Kapoor]]}}\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Filmfare Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]]\n| {{sort|Sharma|[[Anushka Sharma]]}}\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Filmfare Award for Best Music Director|Best Music Director]]\n| {{sort|Pritam|[[Pritam]]}}\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Filmfare Award for Best Lyricist|Best Lyricist]]\n| {{sort|Bhattacharya|[[Amitabh Bhattacharya]]}} for \"Channa Mereya\"\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| [[Filmfare Award for Best Male Playback Singer|Best Playback Singer \u2013 Male]]\n| {{sort|Singh|[[Arijit Singh]]}} for \"Ae Dil Hai Mushkil\"\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Filmfare RD Burman Award for New Music Talent|RD Burman Award for New Music Talent]]\n|{{sort|Mishra|Amit Mishra}} for \"Bulleya\"\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Filmfare Award for Best Female Playback Singer|Best Playback Singer \u2013 Female]]\n| {{sort|Gandhi|[[Jonita Gandhi]]}} for \"The Breakup Song\"\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\" scope=\"row\" | [[Screen Awards]]\n| rowspan=\"6\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | 4 December 2016\n| [[Screen Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]]\n| {{sort|Kapoor|Ranbir Kapoor}}\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"6\" style=\"text-align:center;\" |<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/22nd-star-screen-awards-2016-pink-amitabh-bachchan-alia-bhatt/1/826924.html|title=Star Screen Awards 2016 winners list|date=5 December 2016|accessdate=15 January 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Screen Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]]\n| {{sort|Sharma|Anushka Sharma}}\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n|-\n| [[Screen Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]]\n| {{sort|Rai Bachchan|[[Aishwarya Rai Bachchan]]}}\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Screen Award for Best Music Director|Best Music Director]]\n| {{sort|Pritam|Pritam}}\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Screen Award for Best Male Playback|Best Male Playback]]\n| {{sort|Mishra|Amit Mishra}} for \"Bulleya\"\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Screen Award for Best Lyricist|Best Lyricist]]\n| {{sort|Bhattacharya|Amitabh Bhattacharya}} for \"Ae Dil Hai Mushkil\"\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"13\" scope=\"row\" | [[Stardust Awards]]\n| rowspan=\"13\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | 20 December 2016\n| [[Stardust Award for Best Film|Best Film]]\n| ''Ae Dil Hai Mushkil''\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"13\" style=\"text-align:center;\" |<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/features/nominations-stardust-awards-2016/|title=Nominations for Stardust Awards 2016|date=19 December 2016|accessdate=16 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bollywoodlife.com/news-gossip/stardust-awards-2016-full-winners-list-shah-rukh-khan-priyanka-chopra-aishwarya-rai-bachchan-win-big/|title=Stardust Awards 2016 Full Winners List|date=20 December 2016|accessdate=16 January 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Stardust Award for Best Director|Best Director]]\n| {{sort|Johar|Karan Johar}}\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Stardust Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]]\n| {{sort|Kapoor|Ranbir Kapoor}}\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Stardust A