st Music Director\n| {{sort|Pritam|Pritam}}\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| Best Lyricist\n| {{sort|Bhattacharya|Amitabh Bhattacharya}} for \"Channa Mereya\"\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| {{sort|Bhattacharya|Amitabh Bhattacharya}} for \"Ae Dil Hai Mushkil\"\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Best Playback Singer (Male)\n| {{sort|Singh|Arijit Singh}} for \"Channa Mereya\"\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| {{sort|Singh|Arijit Singh}} for \"Ae Dil Hai Mushkil\"\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Playback Singer (Female)\n| {{sort|Gandhi|[[Jonita Gandhi]]}} for \"The Breakup Song\"\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"18\" scope=\"row\" | [[Mirchi Music Awards]]\n| rowspan=\"18\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[9th Mirchi Music Awards|18 February 2017]]\n| rowspan=\"4\" | [[Mirchi Music Award for Song of The Year|Song of the Year]]\n| \"[[Ae Dil Hai Mushkil (song)]]\"\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"18\" style=\"text-align:center;\" |<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mirchimusicawards.com/hindi-2016/nominations/|title=Nomination - Mirchi Music Awards|website=MMAMirchiMusicAwards|access-date=2018-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mirchimusicawards.com/hindi-2016/winners/|title=Winners -Mirchi Music Awards|website=MMAMirchiMusicAwards|access-date=2018-03-21}}</ref>\n|-\n| \"Bulleya\"\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| \"[[Channa Mereya]]\"\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| \"Channa Mereya (Unplugged)\"\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Mirchi Music Award for Album of The Year|Album of the Year]]\n| Pritam and Amitabh Bhattacharya\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | [[Mirchi Music Award for Male Vocalist of The Year|Male Vocalist of the Year]]\n| [[Amit Mishra (singer)|Amit Mishra]] for \"Bulleya\"\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Arijit Singh for \"Ae Dil Hai Mushkil\"\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Arijit Singh for \"Channa Mereya\"\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Mirchi Music Award for Female Vocalist of The Year|Female Vocalist of the Year]]\n| Jonita Gandhi for \"\"The Breakup Song\"\"\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Shilpa Rao for \"Bulleya\"\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | [[Mirchi Music Award for Music Composer of The Year|Music Composer of the Year]]\n| Pritam for \"Ae Dil Hai Mushkil\"\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Pritam  for \"Bulleya\"\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Pritam for \"Channa Mereya\"\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | [[Mirchi Music Award for Lyricist of The Year|Lyricist of the Year]]\n| Amitabh Bhattacharya for \"Ae Dil Hai Mushkil\"\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Amitabh Bhattacharya for \"Bulleya\"\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Amitabh Bhattacharya for \"Channa Mereya\"\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Best Song Engineer (Recording & Mixing)\n| Shadab Rayeen, [[Sunny M.R.]] & Ashwin Kulkarni for \"Bulleya\"\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Background Score\n| Pritam\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{IMDb title|4559006}}\n*{{Facebook|AeDilHaiMushkil}}\n\n\n[[Category:2016 films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Films featuring songs by Pritam]]\n[[Category:Indian romantic drama films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Karan Johar]]\n[[Category:Indian romance films]]\n[[Category:2010s Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:Films set in Lucknow]]\n[[Category:Films set in London]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Mandawa]]\n[[Category:Fox Star Studios films]]\n", "name_user": "YortoboL", "label": "safe", "comment": "removed unnecessary hyperlink", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ae_Dil_Hai_Mushkil"}
{"title_page": "Hellaro", "text_new": "{{short description|2019 Indian Gujarati period film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Hellaro\n| image          = Hellaro film poster.jpg\n| caption        = Official poster\n| director       = Abhishek Shah\n| producer       = Ashish Patel <br/> Nirav Patel<br/> Aayush Patel<br/> Abhishek Shah<br/> Mit Jani<br/> Prateek Gupta\n| story          = Abhishek Shah \n| screenplay     = Abhishek Shah <br/>Prateek Gupta <br/> [[Saumya Joshi]] <br/> {{small|(Dialogues & Lyrics)}}\n| starring       = {{plainlist|\n*Jayesh More\n*[[Shraddha Dangar]]\n*Brinda Trivedi Nayak\n*Shachi Joshi\n*Neelam Panchal\n*Tejal Panchasara\n*Kausambi Bhatt\n*Kishan Gadhavi\n}}\n| music          = Mehul Surti\n| cinematography = Tribhuvan Babu Sadineni\n| editing        = Prateek Gupta\n| studio         = Harfanmaula Films\n| runtime        = 121 minutes\n| country        = India\n| language       = Gujarati\n| released       = {{film date|df=y|2019|11|8}}\n| based on       = \n| distributor    = \n| budget         = {{estimation|{{INRConvert|5|c}}}}<ref name=\"OI\"/>\n| gross          = {{estimation|{{INRConvert|16|c}}}}<ref name=\"OI\"/><ref name=\"numb2\"/>\n}}\n'''''Hellaro''''' ({{trans|The outburst}}) is a 2019 Indian [[Gujarati cinema|Gujarati]] [[period drama]] film co-written and directed by Abhishek Shah and produced by Ashish Patel, Nirav Patel, Aayush Patel, Prateek Gupta, Mit Jani and Abhishek Shah under the banner of Saarthi Productions and Harfanmaula films. The film having ensemble cast of Jayesh More, [[Shraddha Dangar]], Brinda Trivedi Nayak, Shachi Joshi, Niilam Paanchal, Tejal Panchasara and Kausambi Bhatt, marks the directorial debut of Abhishek Shah.\n\nThe film revolves around a group of women living in Kutch in 1970s.\n\n''Hellaro'' won the [[National Film Award for Best Feature Film]] at the [[66th National Film Awards]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Staff |first1=Scroll |title=National Awards: Aditya Dhar gets best director for \u2018Uri\u2019, Gujarati movie \u2018Hellaro\u2019 wins Best Film |url=https://scroll.in/latest/933356/national-awards-aditya-dhar-gets-best-director-for-uri-gujarati-movie-hellaro-wins-best-film |accessdate=9 August 2019 |work=Scroll.in |date=9 August 2019}}</ref> It was officially selected as the opening film at Indian Panorama, at [[50th International Film Festival of India]] (IFFI).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mid-day.com/articles/gujarati-film-hellaro-to-be-iffi-goa-opening-feature/21859186|title=Gujarati film Hellaro to be IFFI Goa opening feature|date=7 October 2019|website=mid-day}}</ref> It is also nominated for the best debut feature film of a director at the film festival.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ani/indian-films-hellaro-uyare-to-vie-for-best-debut-feature-award-at-iffi-119102000171_1.html|title=Indian films 'Hellaro', 'Uyare' to vie for Best Debut Feature Award at IFFI|date=20 October 2019|via=Business Standard}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.aninews.in/news/national/general-news/indian-films-hellaro-uyare-to-vie-for-best-debut-feature-award-at-iffi20191020112156/|title=Indian films 'Hellaro', 'Uyare' to vie for Best Debut Feature Award at IFFI|website=www.aninews.in}}</ref> The film has been theatrically released in India on 8 November 2019 to positive reviews.\n\n==Synopsis==\nIn 1975, a young girl named Manjhri is married off to a small village in the middle of nowhere in the [[Rann of Kutch]]. There, she joins a group of women shackled by patriarchal mandates. Their only escape from the suppression is when they go out to fetch water at a distant waterbody every morning. Other than those few hours everyday, their lives are bound by the rules made by men which they have to abide by. One day, while on their way to fetch water, they find someone in the middle of the desert and their lives are changed forever.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://ahmedabadmirror.indiatimes.com/ahmedabad/others/gujs-hellaro-is-nations-best/articleshow/70612256.cms|title=Guj\u2019s \u2018Hellaro\u2019 is nation\u2019s best|date=2018-08-10|website=Ahmedabad Mirror|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-08-12}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* [[Shraddha Dangar]] as Manjhri\n* Jayesh More as Mulji, a drummer\n* Tejal Panchasara as Gomti\n* Shailesh Prajapati as Mukhi\n* Maulik Nayak as Bhaglo\n* Aarjav Trivedi as Arjan\n* Brinda Trivedi Nayak\n* Tarjani Bhadla as Gauri\n* Niilam Paanchal as Leela\n* Kaushambi Bhatt as Champa\n* Swati Dave\n* Denisha Ghumra as Radha\n* Aakash Zala as Joraavar\n* Rajan Thakar\n* Kishan Gadhvi\n* Kamlesh Parmar\n* Sachi Joshi\n* Riddhi Yadav as Kanchan\n* Jagruti Thakore\n* Kamini Panchal\n* Ekta Bachwani\n* Parva Bhatt<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/ahmedabad/hellaro-1st-gujarati-film-to-win-top-national-award/articleshow/70612338.cms|title=\u2018Hellaro\u2019 1st Gujarati film to win top national award|last=|first=|date=2019-08-10|website=The Times of India|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-08-12}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.republicworld.com/entertainment-news/others/hellaro-cast-all-about-the-hellaro-gujarati-movie-cast-to-check-out|title=Hellaro cast: All about the Hellaro Gujarati movie cast that you must check out|last=World|first=Republic|website=Republic World|access-date=2019-11-19}}</ref>\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\nThe debut director and co-writer Abhishek Shah stated that the story was inspired from folklore of the Vrajvani village in Kutch and real-life instances of [[patriarchy]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/express-sunday-eye/dance-like-a-woman-gujarati-film-garba-hellaro-abhishek-shah-national-award-for-best-feature-film-iffi-goa-6107300/|title=The importance of Garba in National Award-winning Gujarati film Hellaro|date=2019-11-10|website=The Indian Express|language=en-IN|access-date=2019-11-18}}</ref><ref name=\":4\" /> Prateek Gupta co-wrote screenplay, edited, and co-produced the film while also serving as the Associate Director. Playwright and poet [[Saumya Joshi]] wrote lyrics, additional screenplay, and dialogues. Mehul Surti composed the music.<ref name=\":0\"/> Ashish Patel, Nirav Patel, Aayush Patel, Abhishek Shah, Mit Jani, and  Prateek Gupta produced the film under the banner of Saarthi Productions and Harfanmaula films. Aayush Patel and Mit Jani helmed as creative and executive producers.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nA set of village with fifteen Bhunga (traditional houses), a town square and a temple was created in [[Rann of Kutch]] near Kuran village where the film was shot.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india-today-insight/story/how-a-little-known-gujarati-movie-won-the-best-feature-film-award-1580593-2019-08-14|title=How a little-known Gujarati movie won the best feature film award|last=Singh|first=Suhani|date=2019-08-14|website=India Today|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-19}}</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Hellaro\n| type       = soundtrack\n| artist     = Mehul Surti\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   =  {{start date|2019|10|18|df=y}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jiosaavn.com/album/hellaro/KKkVTfOKhfQ_|title=Hellaro |publisher=[[Saavn]]}}</ref>\n| recorded   = 2018\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Feature film soundtrack]]\n| length     = 18:44\n| language   = [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]]\n| label      = Saarthi Productions LLP\n| producer   = \n| misc = {{External media\n| audio1 = {{YouTube|qcl5Cn6R0wY|Official Audio Jukebox}}}}\n}}\n\n{{tracklist\n| headline =Track listing\n| extra_column = Singer(s)\n| total_length = 18:44\n|all_music= Mehul Surti\n|all_lyrics= [[Saumya Joshi]]\n\n| title1 = Asvaar\n| extra1 = [[Aishwarya Majmudar]], [[Mooralala Marwada]]\n| length1 = 4:03\n\n| title2 = Mara Haiyaa Na Zadawani\n| extra2 = [[Shruti Pathak]], Aditya Gadhavi (Backing vocals)\n| length2 = 5:01\n\n\n| title3 = Sapna Vinani Raat\n| extra3 = Aditya Gadhavi\n| length3 = 5:30\n\n| title4 = Vaagyo Re Dhol\n| extra4 = [[Bhoomi Trivedi]]\n| length4 = 4:10\n\n}}\n\n==Release==\nThe official trailer of the film was unveiled by producers on 10 October 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://youtube.com/watch?v=qb8uOylK3R4|title=Hellaro &#124; Official Trailer &#124; Abhishek Shah - Jayesh More &#124; Shraddha Dangar &#124; 8th November 2019|publisher=Hellaro |website=YouTube|date=10 October 2019}}</ref> It was released in theatres on 8 November 2019.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india-today-insight/story/how-a-little-known-gujarati-movie-won-the-best-feature-film-award-1580593-2019-08-14|title=How a little-known Gujarati movie won the best feature film award|last=Singh|first=Suhani|date=2019-08-14|website=India Today|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-08-15}}</ref>\n\n==Reception and accolades==\n\n=== Critical response ===\nThe film was universally acclaimed by the critics. Abhimanyu Joshi of ''[[The Times of India]]'' rated it 4 out of 5. He praised the film's direction, story, screenplay, acting, cinematography, music, and choreography, further stating that the film justly deserves the National Award it received and fulfills expectations.<ref>{{Citation|title=Hellaro Movie Review: Hellaro, a celluloid celebration of breaking free|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/gujarati/movie-reviews/hellaro/movie-review/71971460.cms|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref> Namrata Joshi writing for ''[[The Hindu]]'' praised the story, direction, production, and cinematography. She further added that the film \"questions [[patriarchy]] while celebrating the colours and culture of Gujarat\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/entertainment/movies/hellaro-movie-review-of-song-and-dance-leading-to-flight-and-freedom/article29951712.ece|title=\u2018Hellaro\u2019 movie review: Of song and dance leading to flight and freedom|last=Joshi|first=Namrata|date=2019-11-12|work=The Hindu|access-date=2019-11-13|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> Jigar Ganatra of Mumbai Live called it \"masterpiece\" and rated 4.5 out of 5.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mumbailive.com/en/entertainment/hellaro-movie-review-gujarati-film-national-award-2019-by-abhishek-shah-on-garba-in-kutch-41607|title=Hellaro Movie Review: Hellaro is a 'masterpiece' from debutant director Abhishek Shah|website=Mumbai Live|language=en|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref> ''Parsi Times'' rated it 3.5 out of 5.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://parsi-times.com/2019/11/film-review-hellaro/|title=Film Review: Hellaro|last=Katrak|first=Hoshang K.|date=2019-11-09|website=Parsi Times|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref> Delnaz Divecha writing for BookMyShow noted that the film's presentation of the subjects of patriarchy, casteism, and superstition connects the audience, and further praised the film's performances and choreography. She also pointed that \"some customs may seem outdated but still happen to be the reality of many rural women\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://in.bookmyshow.com/entertainment/movies/reviews/gujrati-reviews/hellaro-film-review-national-award/|title=[Review] Hellaro Beautifully Explores The Idea of Freedom Through Dance|last=Divecha|first=Delnaz|date=2019-11-09|website=BookMyShow|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref> Jinal Bhatt of Mashable India rated it 4.5 out of 5.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://in.mashable.com/entertainment/8612/hellaro-review-a-powerful-journey-from-suppression-to-expression-stomping-patriarchy-on-the-way|title=Hellaro Review: A Powerful Journey From Suppression To Expression, Stomping Patriarchy On The Way|last=Bhatt|first=Jinal|date=2019-11-18|website=Mashable India|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-19}}</ref>\n\nRamesh Tanna of ''[[Kutchmitra]]'' praised the film for its direction, acting, and cinematography, calling it a \"must-watch\" but criticised the false subject of opposition to [[Garba (dance)|garba]] and [[Kutch Embroidery|embroidery]] work, some characterisations, and the lack of [[Kutchi language]] in a film set in Kutch. He also questioned the relevance of the film's subject in contemporary times and pointed to the inaccurate representation of Kutch's local culture and the 1970s.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/ramesh.tanna.5/posts/10156947150392893|title=Ramesh Tanna|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref>\n\n=== Box office ===\nThe film had grossed over {{INRConvert|15|c}} in the box office.<ref name=\"OI\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/film-awards-and-rewards-column-btown/1711984|title=Film awards and rewards (Column: B-Town)|last=|first=|date=2020-02-19|website=Outlook|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-05|agency=IANS}}</ref><ref name=\"BMS\">{{Cite web|url=https://in.bookmyshow.com/movies/box-office/hellaro-box-office-collections/EG00090151|title=Hellaro Collections|last=|first=|date=|website=in.bookmyshow.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref> The film had grossed over $1,41,304 ({{INR|1 crore}}) in overseas market.<ref name=\"numb2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Hellaro-(India)/United-Kingdom|title=Hellaro - Financial Information|last=|first=|date=|website=The Numbers|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/title/tt10469118/credits/?ref_=bo_tt_tab|title=Hellaro|website=Box Office Mojo|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n''Hellaro'' won the [[National Film Award for Best Feature Film]] at the [[66th National Film Awards]]. The thirteen female actresses also won the Special Jury Award  for their performances. It was the first Gujarati film to win the National Film Award for Best Feature Film.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":0\" />\n\n''Hellaro'' was selected as the opening film at the Indian Panorama during the 50th [[International Film Festival of India]] (IFFI), held in November 2019 in [[Goa]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://iffigoa.org/opening-film-indian-panorama-2019/|title=Regional Films \u2018Hellaro\u2019 & \u2018Nooreh\u2019 to open Indian Panorama at IFFI 2019|date=2019-10-06|website=IFFI Goa|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-19}}</ref><ref name=\":5\" /> where it won a special mention from jury for its \"incredible music, colour and choreography.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jagranjosh.com/current-affairs/iffi-2019-full-list-of-winners-particles-best-film-lijo-jose-pellissery-best-director-award-1575006078-1|title=IFFI 2019: Full list of winners; Particles wins Best Film, Lijo Jose Pellissery wins Best Director award\n|date=29 November 2019}}</ref> It is also nominated for the best debut feature film of a director at the film festival.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":7\" /> It was also screened at the 19th River-to-River Florence Indian Film Festival held in Italy in December 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/gujarati/movies/news/gujarati-film-hellaro-to-be-screened-in-delhi/articleshow/73609363.cms|title=Gujarati film 'Hellaro' to be screened in Delhi|last=|first=|date=2020-01-25|website=The Times of India|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-05}}</ref> \n\n==Controversy==\nA police complaint under [[Scheduled Caste and Scheduled Tribe (Prevention of Atrocities) Act, 1989|Atrocities Act]] was filed against the film's producer, director, and writer for use of term [[Harijan]] in the film's dialogue. According to the complainant Jamnaben Vegda, the term is considered derogatory by the [[Scheduled Castes and Scheduled Tribes|Scheduled Caste]] people .<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/other-states/fir-against-makers-of-national-award-film-hellaro/article29959036.ece|title=FIR against makers of national award film \u2018Hellaro\u2019|date=2019-11-13|work=The Hindu|access-date=2019-11-13|others=PTI|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links==\n* {{IMDb title}}\n\n{{National Film Award Best Feature Film}}\n\n[[Category:Gujarati-language films]]\n[[Category:2019 films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Films set in Gujarat]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Gujarat]]\n[[Category:Best Feature Film National Film Award winners]]\n[[Category:Special Jury Award (feature film) National Film Award winners]]\n[[Category:Directorial debut films]] \n[[Category:Directorial debut film awards]]\n[[Category:Period films]]\nhttps://fantasiabarrinoofficial.com/2020/03/31/hellaro-movie-download/\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2019 Indian Gujarati period film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Hellaro\n| image          = Hellaro film poster.jpg\n| caption        = Official poster\n| director       = Abhishek Shah\n| producer       = Ashish Patel <br/> Nirav Patel<br/> Aayush Patel<br/> Abhishek Shah<br/> Mit Jani<br/> Prateek Gupta\n| story          = Abhishek Shah \n| screenplay     = Abhishek Shah <br/>Prateek Gupta <br/> [[Saumya Joshi]] <br/> {{small|(Dialogues & Lyrics)}}\n| starring       = {{plainlist|\n*Jayesh More\n*[[Shraddha Dangar]]\n*Brinda Trivedi Nayak\n*Shachi Joshi\n*Neelam Panchal\n*Tejal Panchasara\n*Kausambi Bhatt\n*Kishan Gadhavi\n}}\n| music          = Mehul Surti\n| cinematography = Tribhuvan Babu Sadineni\n| editing        = Prateek Gupta\n| studio         = Harfanmaula Films\n| runtime        = 121 minutes\n| country        = India\n| language       = Gujarati\n| released       = {{film date|df=y|2019|11|8}}\n| based on       = \n| distributor    = \n| budget         = {{estimation|{{INRConvert|5|c}}}}<ref name=\"OI\"/>\n| gross          = {{estimation|{{INRConvert|16|c}}}}<ref name=\"OI\"/><ref name=\"numb2\"/>\n}}\n'''''Hellaro''''' ({{trans|The outburst}}) is a 2019 Indian [[Gujarati cinema|Gujarati]] [[period drama]] film co-written and directed by Abhishek Shah and produced by Ashish Patel, Nirav Patel, Aayush Patel, Prateek Gupta, Mit Jani and Abhishek Shah under the banner of Saarthi Productions and Harfanmaula films. The film having ensemble cast of Jayesh More, [[Shraddha Dangar]], Brinda Trivedi Nayak, Shachi Joshi, Niilam Paanchal, Tejal Panchasara and Kausambi Bhatt, marks the directorial debut of Abhishek Shah.\n\nThe film revolves around a group of women living in Kutch in 1970s.\n\n''Hellaro'' won the [[National Film Award for Best Feature Film]] at the [[66th National Film Awards]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Staff |first1=Scroll |title=National Awards: Aditya Dhar gets best director for \u2018Uri\u2019, Gujarati movie \u2018Hellaro\u2019 wins Best Film |url=https://scroll.in/latest/933356/national-awards-aditya-dhar-gets-best-director-for-uri-gujarati-movie-hellaro-wins-best-film |accessdate=9 August 2019 |work=Scroll.in |date=9 August 2019}}</ref> It was officially selected as the opening film at Indian Panorama, at [[50th International Film Festival of India]] (IFFI).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mid-day.com/articles/gujarati-film-hellaro-to-be-iffi-goa-opening-feature/21859186|title=Gujarati film Hellaro to be IFFI Goa opening feature|date=7 October 2019|website=mid-day}}</ref> It is also nominated for the best debut feature film of a director at the film festival.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ani/indian-films-hellaro-uyare-to-vie-for-best-debut-feature-award-at-iffi-119102000171_1.html|title=Indian films 'Hellaro', 'Uyare' to vie for Best Debut Feature Award at IFFI|date=20 October 2019|via=Business Standard}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.aninews.in/news/national/general-news/indian-films-hellaro-uyare-to-vie-for-best-debut-feature-award-at-iffi20191020112156/|title=Indian films 'Hellaro', 'Uyare' to vie for Best Debut Feature Award at IFFI|website=www.aninews.in}}</ref> The film has been theatrically released in India on 8 November 2019 to positive reviews.\n\n==Synopsis==\nIn 1975, a young girl named Manjhri is married off to a small village in the middle of nowhere in the [[Rann of Kutch]]. There, she joins a group of women shackled by patriarchal mandates. Their only escape from the suppression is when they go out to fetch water at a distant waterbody every morning. Other than those few hours everyday, their lives are bound by the rules made by men which they have to abide by. One day, while on their way to fetch water, they find someone in the middle of the desert and their lives are changed forever.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://ahmedabadmirror.indiatimes.com/ahmedabad/others/gujs-hellaro-is-nations-best/articleshow/70612256.cms|title=Guj\u2019s \u2018Hellaro\u2019 is nation\u2019s best|date=2018-08-10|website=Ahmedabad Mirror|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-08-12}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* [[Shraddha Dangar]] as Manjhri\n* Jayesh More as Mulji, a drummer\n* Tejal Panchasara as Gomti\n* Shailesh Prajapati as Mukhi\n* Maulik Nayak as Bhaglo\n* Aarjav Trivedi as Arjan\n* Brinda Trivedi Nayak\n* Tarjani Bhadla as Gauri\n* Niilam Paanchal as Leela\n* Kaushambi Bhatt as Champa\n* Swati Dave\n* Denisha Ghumra as Radha\n* Aakash Zala as Joraavar\n* Rajan Thakar\n* Kishan Gadhvi\n* Kamlesh Parmar\n* Sachi Joshi\n* Riddhi Yadav as Kanchan\n* Jagruti Thakore\n* Kamini Panchal\n* Ekta Bachwani\n* Parva Bhatt<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/ahmedabad/hellaro-1st-gujarati-film-to-win-top-national-award/articleshow/70612338.cms|title=\u2018Hellaro\u2019 1st Gujarati film to win top national award|last=|first=|date=2019-08-10|website=The Times of India|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-08-12}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.republicworld.com/entertainment-news/others/hellaro-cast-all-about-the-hellaro-gujarati-movie-cast-to-check-out|title=Hellaro cast: All about the Hellaro Gujarati movie cast that you must check out|last=World|first=Republic|website=Republic World|access-date=2019-11-19}}</ref>\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\nThe debut director and co-writer Abhishek Shah stated that the story was inspired from folklore of the Vrajvani village in Kutch and real-life instances of [[patriarchy]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/express-sunday-eye/dance-like-a-woman-gujarati-film-garba-hellaro-abhishek-shah-national-award-for-best-feature-film-iffi-goa-6107300/|title=The importance of Garba in National Award-winning Gujarati film Hellaro|date=2019-11-10|website=The Indian Express|language=en-IN|access-date=2019-11-18}}</ref><ref name=\":4\" /> Prateek Gupta co-wrote screenplay, edited, and co-produced the film while also serving as the Associate Director. Playwright and poet [[Saumya Joshi]] wrote lyrics, additional screenplay, and dialogues. Mehul Surti composed the music.<ref name=\":0\"/> Ashish Patel, Nirav Patel, Aayush Patel, Abhishek Shah, Mit Jani, and  Prateek Gupta produced the film under the banner of Saarthi Productions and Harfanmaula films. Aayush Patel and Mit Jani helmed as creative and executive producers.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nA set of village with fifteen Bhunga (traditional houses), a town square and a temple was created in [[Rann of Kutch]] near Kuran village where the film was shot.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india-today-insight/story/how-a-little-known-gujarati-movie-won-the-best-feature-film-award-1580593-2019-08-14|title=How a little-known Gujarati movie won the best feature film award|last=Singh|first=Suhani|date=2019-08-14|website=India Today|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-19}}</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Hellaro\n| type       = soundtrack\n| artist     = Mehul Surti\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   =  {{start date|2019|10|18|df=y}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jiosaavn.com/album/hellaro/KKkVTfOKhfQ_|title=Hellaro |publisher=[[Saavn]]}}</ref>\n| recorded   = 2018\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Feature film soundtrack]]\n| length     = 18:44\n| language   = [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]]\n| label      = Saarthi Productions LLP\n| producer   = \n| misc = {{External media\n| audio1 = {{YouTube|qcl5Cn6R0wY|Official Audio Jukebox}}}}\n}}\n\n{{tracklist\n| headline =Track listing\n| extra_column = Singer(s)\n| total_length = 18:44\n|all_music= Mehul Surti\n|all_lyrics= [[Saumya Joshi]]\n\n| title1 = Asvaar\n| extra1 = [[Aishwarya Majmudar]], [[Mooralala Marwada]]\n| length1 = 4:03\n\n| title2 = Mara Haiyaa Na Zadawani\n| extra2 = [[Shruti Pathak]], Aditya Gadhavi (Backing vocals)\n| length2 = 5:01\n\n\n| title3 = Sapna Vinani Raat\n| extra3 = Aditya Gadhavi\n| length3 = 5:30\n\n| title4 = Vaagyo Re Dhol\n| extra4 = [[Bhoomi Trivedi]]\n| length4 = 4:10\n\n}}\n\n==Release==\nThe official trailer of the film was unveiled by producers on 10 October 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://youtube.com/watch?v=qb8uOylK3R4|title=Hellaro &#124; Official Trailer &#124; Abhishek Shah - Jayesh More &#124; Shraddha Dangar &#124; 8th November 2019|publisher=Hellaro |website=YouTube|date=10 October 2019}}</ref> It was released in theatres on 8 November 2019.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india-today-insight/story/how-a-little-known-gujarati-movie-won-the-best-feature-film-award-1580593-2019-08-14|title=How a little-known Gujarati movie won the best feature film award|last=Singh|first=Suhani|date=2019-08-14|website=India Today|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-08-15}}</ref>\n\n==Reception and accolades==\n\n=== Critical response ===\nThe film was universally acclaimed by the critics. Abhimanyu Joshi of ''[[The Times of India]]'' rated it 4 out of 5. He praised the film's direction, story, screenplay, acting, cinematography, music, and choreography, further stating that the film justly deserves the National Award it received and fulfills expectations.<ref>{{Citation|title=Hellaro Movie Review: Hellaro, a celluloid celebration of breaking free|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/gujarati/movie-reviews/hellaro/movie-review/71971460.cms|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref> Namrata Joshi writing for ''[[The Hindu]]'' praised the story, direction, production, and cinematography. She further added that the film \"questions [[patriarchy]] while celebrating the colours and culture of Gujarat\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/entertainment/movies/hellaro-movie-review-of-song-and-dance-leading-to-flight-and-freedom/article29951712.ece|title=\u2018Hellaro\u2019 movie review: Of song and dance leading to flight and freedom|last=Joshi|first=Namrata|date=2019-11-12|work=The Hindu|access-date=2019-11-13|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> Jigar Ganatra of Mumbai Live called it \"masterpiece\" and rated 4.5 out of 5.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mumbailive.com/en/entertainment/hellaro-movie-review-gujarati-film-national-award-2019-by-abhishek-shah-on-garba-in-kutch-41607|title=Hellaro Movie Review: Hellaro is a 'masterpiece' from debutant director Abhishek Shah|website=Mumbai Live|language=en|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref> ''Parsi Times'' rated it 3.5 out of 5.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://parsi-times.com/2019/11/film-review-hellaro/|title=Film Review: Hellaro|last=Katrak|first=Hoshang K.|date=2019-11-09|website=Parsi Times|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref> Delnaz Divecha writing for BookMyShow noted that the film's presentation of the subjects of patriarchy, casteism, and superstition connects the audience, and further praised the film's performances and choreography. She also pointed that \"some customs may seem outdated but still happen to be the reality of many rural women\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://in.bookmyshow.com/entertainment/movies/reviews/gujrati-reviews/hellaro-film-review-national-award/|title=[Review] Hellaro Beautifully Explores The Idea of Freedom Through Dance|last=Divecha|first=Delnaz|date=2019-11-09|website=BookMyShow|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref> Jinal Bhatt of Mashable India rated it 4.5 out of 5.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://in.mashable.com/entertainment/8612/hellaro-review-a-powerful-journey-from-suppression-to-expression-stomping-patriarchy-on-the-way|title=Hellaro Review: A Powerful Journey From Suppression To Expression, Stomping Patriarchy On The Way|last=Bhatt|first=Jinal|date=2019-11-18|website=Mashable India|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-19}}</ref>\n\nRamesh Tanna of ''[[Kutchmitra]]'' praised the film for its direction, acting, and cinematography, calling it a \"must-watch\" but criticised the false subject of opposition to [[Garba (dance)|garba]] and [[Kutch Embroidery|embroidery]] work, some characterisations, and the lack of [[Kutchi language]] in a film set in Kutch. He also questioned the relevance of the film's subject in contemporary times and pointed to the inaccurate representation of Kutch's local culture and the 1970s.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/ramesh.tanna.5/posts/10156947150392893|title=Ramesh Tanna|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref>\n\n=== Box office ===\nThe film had grossed over {{INRConvert|15|c}} in the box office.<ref name=\"OI\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/film-awards-and-rewards-column-btown/1711984|title=Film awards and rewards (Column: B-Town)|last=|first=|date=2020-02-19|website=Outlook|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-05|agency=IANS}}</ref><ref name=\"BMS\">{{Cite web|url=https://in.bookmyshow.com/movies/box-office/hellaro-box-office-collections/EG00090151|title=Hellaro Collections|last=|first=|date=|website=in.bookmyshow.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref> The film had grossed over $1,41,304 ({{INR|1 crore}}) in overseas market.<ref name=\"numb2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Hellaro-(India)/United-Kingdom|title=Hellaro - Financial Information|last=|first=|date=|website=The Numbers|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/title/tt10469118/credits/?ref_=bo_tt_tab|title=Hellaro|website=Box Office Mojo|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n''Hellaro'' won the [[National Film Award for Best Feature Film]] at the [[66th National Film Awards]]. The thirteen female actresses also won the Special Jury Award  for their performances. It was the first Gujarati film to win the National Film Award for Best Feature Film.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":0\" />\n\n''Hellaro'' was selected as the opening film at the Indian Panorama during the 50th [[International Film Festival of India]] (IFFI), held in November 2019 in [[Goa]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://iffigoa.org/opening-film-indian-panorama-2019/|title=Regional Films \u2018Hellaro\u2019 & \u2018Nooreh\u2019 to open Indian Panorama at IFFI 2019|date=2019-10-06|website=IFFI Goa|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-19}}</ref><ref name=\":5\" /> where it won a special mention from jury for its \"incredible music, colour and choreography.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jagranjosh.com/current-affairs/iffi-2019-full-list-of-winners-particles-best-film-lijo-jose-pellissery-best-director-award-1575006078-1|title=IFFI 2019: Full list of winners; Particles wins Best Film, Lijo Jose Pellissery wins Best Director award\n|date=29 November 2019}}</ref> It is also nominated for the best debut feature film of a director at the film festival.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":7\" /> It was also screened at the 19th River-to-River Florence Indian Film Festival held in Italy in December 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/gujarati/movies/news/gujarati-film-hellaro-to-be-screened-in-delhi/articleshow/73609363.cms|title=Gujarati film 'Hellaro' to be screened in Delhi|last=|first=|date=2020-01-25|website=The Times of India|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-05}}</ref> \n\n==Controversy==\nA police complaint under [[Scheduled Caste and Scheduled Tribe (Prevention of Atrocities) Act, 1989|Atrocities Act]] was filed against the film's producer, director, and writer for use of term [[Harijan]] in the film's dialogue. According to the complainant Jamnaben Vegda, the term is considered derogatory by the [[Scheduled Castes and Scheduled Tribes|Scheduled Caste]] people .<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/other-states/fir-against-makers-of-national-award-film-hellaro/article29959036.ece|title=FIR against makers of national award film \u2018Hellaro\u2019|date=2019-11-13|work=The Hindu|access-date=2019-11-13|others=PTI|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links==\n* {{IMDb title}}\n\n{{National Film Award Best Feature Film}}\n\n[[Category:Gujarati-language films]]\n[[Category:2019 films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Films set in Gujarat]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Gujarat]]\n[[Category:Best Feature Film National Film Award winners]]\n[[Category:Special Jury Award (feature film) National Film Award winners]]\n[[Category:Directorial debut films]] \n[[Category:Directorial debut film awards]]\n[[Category:Period films]]\n", "name_user": "Kapil Khatik", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eExternal links:I have placed some information above and placed my website link in External Links section for users to get more information about the topic on my blog where all the informations are available.)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hellaro"}
{"title_page": "Meira Paibi", "text_new": "{{Use Indian English|date=July 2016}}{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}'''Meira Paibi''' (Women torch bearers) is a women's [[social movement]] in the [[States and union territories of India|Indian state]] of [[Manipur]]. Referred to as the \"guardians of civil society\", Meira Paibi dates to 1977 in  present [[Kakching district]]. It derives its name from the flaming torches which the women carry while marching through city streets, often at night. They do so both as a patrol, and in protest, seeking redress against human rights violations committed by paramilitary and armed forces units against the innocent. Contextualized, Meira Paibi was founded at a time when the people of Manipur were fighting for self-determination, political autonomy, and independence. \n\nAccording to ''[[The Times of India]]'', Meira Paibi is the \"largest grassroots, civilian movement fighting state atrocities and human rights violations in Manipur\". One of the movement's leaders, A. K. Janaki Leima, says that \"We've been fighting against drug abuse, crimes against women, and the [[Armed Forces (Special Powers) Act|Armed Forces Special Powers Act]] (AFSPA). We will continue to fight these\".\n\n==Background==\nMeira Paibi was established in 1977 in [[Kakching]], [[Thoubal district]], [[Manipur]], India. Meira Paibis are the women \"guardians of civil society\" and they carry flaming torches and march through city streets, frequently at night doing a patrol duty, and as a way of  protest for seeking redress against human rights violations committed by paramilitary and armed forces units against the innocent. The movement evolved at a time when the people of Manipur were fighting for self-determination, political autonomy, and independence.<ref name=\"Thangjom2013\">{{cite journal|last1=Thangjom|first1=Lalzo S.|title=The Role of MEIRA PAIBI in Bringing about Social Change in the Manipuri Society: An Analysis|journal=Journal of Social Welfare & Management|date=October 2013|volume=5|issue=4|pages=235|url=http://connection.ebscohost.com/c/articles/95644768/role-meira-paibi-bringing-about-social-change-manipuri-society-analysis|accessdate=12 March 2016}}</ref>{{Sfn|Parratt|2005|p=157}}<ref name= Sunil2013>{{Cite web|last= Sunil|first= Oinam|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/TOI-Social-Impact-Awards-Lifetime-contribution-Meira-Paibi/articleshow/17963178.cms|title=TOI Social Impact Awards: Lifetime contribution \u2014 Meira Paibi|date=10 January 2013|accessdate=10 March 2016|newspaper=Times of India}}</ref>\n\n==Predecessor movements==\n===Nupi lan===\n{{main|Nupi lan}}\nWomen's social movements in Manipur date to [[British Raj|British rule]]. Two such movements, collectively known as [[Nupi lan]] (Women's War; Women's Uprising),{{sfn|Thomas|2011|p=168}} preceded Meira Paibi. The first one dates to 1904 when women of the [[Imphal]] valley protested against the [[Assistant Superintendent]] of British authority in Manipur because of his directive to collect teak wood from [[Kabaw Valley|Kabas]] to build his house. The women who protested were neighbors in the locality. British authorities brought forces from outside the state to end this women's protest.{{Sfn|Karna|1998|pp=77\u201380}} A second movement occurred in 1939 as protest to forced rice exportation which was causing starvation among the local people.<ref name= Laithangbam>{{Cite news|last=Laithangbam|first=Iboyaima|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/other-states/women-vigilantes-of-manipur-to-observe-meira-paibi-day-on-december-29/article6563476.ece|title=Women vigilantes of Manipur|date=4 November 2014|newspaper=The Hindu}}</ref> Women, nearly 99% of them, protested peacefully, submitting a petition to the [[Durbar (court)|Durbar]] (government authority). The movement forced closure of rice mills and eventually proved successful in halting the exportation of rice.{{Sfn|Karna|1998|pp=77\u201380}} Nupi Lan became the forerunner in introducing reforms in the state after [[World War II]].<ref name=Yen/> 12 December is observed annually by Meira Paibi as \"Women's War Day\" commemorating the events of 1939.<ref name= Laithangbam/>\n\n===Nisha Bandis===\nThe Nisha Bandis women's movement developed in the late 1970s. Its origins are attributed to [[Meitei people|Meitei]] women's activism combating alcoholism and drug addiction.<ref name= Laithangbam/> The women held night marches in the streets of Imphal and elsewhere in Manipur carrying lanterns, chastising the intoxicated, and setting fire to liquor shops. Their actions lead to the introduction of [[prohibition]] laws in the state.<ref name= Sunil2013/> The late 1970s was a period of civil unrest,<ref name=\"Malindog2014\">{{cite web|last1=Malindog|first1=Anna|title=The Role of Women in Self-Determination Movements|url=http://kashmirwatch.com/the-role-of-women-in-self-determination-movements/|accessdate=12 March 2016|date=2 December 2014}}</ref> which established an underground insurgency movement in Manipur. The [[Armed Forces (Special Powers) Act#Armed Forces Special Powers (Assam and Manipur) Act, 1958|Armed Forces Special Powers Assam and Manipur Act 1958]] permitted paramilitary forces and the police to use unlimited power in dealing with insurgency, resulting in the arrest, torture, and deaths of many innocent young people. The Nisha Bandis became socially active with vigilante activities, protests and marches through the streets of Imphal and elsewhere in the state.{{Sfn|Karna|1998|pp=77\u201380}}<ref name=\"Malindog2014\" />\n\n==Establishment==\n{{Quote box\n | quote  =\"The Manipuri story indicates that active participation by women in public affairs can and does contribute to better conditions for children and society at large\". -[[UNICEF]]<ref name=\"Thangjom2013\" />\n | source =\n | width  =25%\n | align  =right\n}}\nThe Nisha Bandis carried ''podons'' (large-wicked kerosene lamps){{sfn|Thomas|Gopalakrishnan|Singh|2001|p=90}} and ''laltain'' ([[Hindi]], lantern) but after switching to flaming torches, they became known as Meira Paibi.<ref name=\"Nepram2005\">{{cite web|last1=Nepram|first1=Binalakshmi|title=A Narrative on the Origin of the Meira Paibis|url=http://www.e-pao.net/epSubPageExtractor.asp?src=leisure.Essays.A_Narrative_on_the_Origin_of_the_Meira_Paibis|publisher=E-Pao|accessdate=12 March 2016|date=9 January 2005}}</ref> The Meitei women torch bearers represented the declaration of a just war defending [[human rights]] in Manipur.<ref name=Yen>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thesangaiexpress.com/30311-is-the-meira-paibi-movement-facing-extinction/|title=Is the Meira Paibi Movement Facing Extinction?|date=15 September 2013|accessdate=10 March 2016|newspaper=The Sangai ExpRess|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160311191148/http://www.thesangaiexpress.com/30311-is-the-meira-paibi-movement-facing-extinction/|archive-date=11 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> Their movement has expanded to hold \"public meetings, demonstrations, road closures and public bandhs or shut down of all essential services, hunger strikes and mass rallies.\"<ref name=Yen/> These women, also known as \"women vigilantes\", stopped army vehicles, rescued innocent youth who were apprehended on false charges, and negotiated their transfer to the police. The Army did not protest as they respected the role of Meitei women in just causes.<ref name= Laithangbam/> The Meira Paibi's movement has become known as the third Nupi Lan.<ref name=\"Nepram2005\" />\n\n==Recognition==\n''Times of India'' awarded the \"TOI Social Impact Awards: Lifetime contribution\" to Meira Paibi and its five leaders, the 83-year-old Thokchom Ramani, Ak Janaki Leima, L Memchoubi Devi, Y Leirik Leima, and Purnimashi Leima.<ref name= Sunil2013/> These five women  -known as \"imas\" or mothers- take an aggressive posture by lowering their traditional ''phanek'' (floral embroidered Meitei sarong), tie it with a cloth belt (''khwang chet''), and cover their shoulders with the formal ''phi'' (embroidered phanek). They also tie a piece of cloth over their head in the form of a [[turban]]. They carry the flaming torch as a symbol of their feminist movement supporting human rights and peace.<ref name= Sunil2013/>\n''Uday '' awarded the\n''Struggle of Meira Paibi''\nTheir fought for the struggle using torch. Many named it with many names but it was Meira Paibi's Movement.\n\n<br />\n\n== Film on Meira Paibi ==\nA short documentary film on Meira Paibi was made in 2018. The film titled, Fireflies is directed by Johnson Rajkumar.<ref>{{Citation|title=Fireflies 2018|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt8011806/|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref>The film focuses on an underrated women\u2019s social movement active in Manipur. Appreciated both by movie buffs and critics, the 6-minute documentary explores the role of women in the conflict-ridden, male-dominated society of Manipur.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eclecticnortheast.in/2018/04/manipuri-activist-makes-documentary-meira-paibis/|title=Manipuri Activist Makes Documentary on Meira Paibis|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>The film articulates the journey of Meira Paibi, a women\u2019s social movement in Manipur, in their struggles to protect the community from atrocities committed by the state.Through powerful testimonies, the film looks into how gender identities are negotiated during times of conflict and violence. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eastmojo.com/manipur/2019/12/20/manipuri-documentary-fireflies-screened-at-kathmandu-film-fest|title=Manipuri documentary \u2018Fireflies\u2019 screened at Kathmandu film fest|last=EastMojo|first=Team|website=EastMojo|language=en|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref>\n\nThe film has got both national and international appreciation. The film had won Best Short Documentary in Arthouse Asia International Film Festival, Kolkata and won second place in short documentary section in Chennai International Short Film Festival.The film had also been selected in several international and national film festivals including Golden Tree International Documentary Film Festival in Frankfurt, Dada Saheb Phalke International Film Festival in Mumbai, Davis Feminist Film Festival in California and Human Rights Short Film Festival in Dhaka, Bangladesh.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eastmojo.com/manipur/2019/12/20/manipuri-documentary-fireflies-screened-at-kathmandu-film-fest|title=Manipuri documentary \u2018Fireflies\u2019 screened at Kathmandu film fest|last=EastMojo|first=Team|website=EastMojo|language=en|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref> Excerpts from the film: [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HoeoEOb6p0s&t=2s Fireflies]\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Ima Market]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Karna|first=Mahendra Narain|title=Social Movements in North-East India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-3FJEfU3swcC&pg=PA77|year=1998|publisher=Indus Publishing|isbn=978-81-7387-083-5}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Parratt|first=John|title=Wounded Land: Politics and Identity in Modern Manipur|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fO4N_FI8jt4C&pg=PA157|year=2005|publisher=Mittal Publications|isbn=978-81-8324-053-6}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last1=Thomas|first1=C. Joshua|last2=Gopalakrishnan|first2=Ramamoorthy|last3=Singh|first3=R. K. Ranjan|title=Constraints In Development Of Manipur|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AFxuAAAAMAAJ|year= 2001|publisher=Regency Publications &#91;for Policy Alternatives for the North-East and Conflict Elimination Awareness&#93;|isbn=978-81-87498-30-8}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Thomas|first=Pradip Ninan|title=Negotiating Communication Rights: Case Studies from India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=W9yGAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA168|year=2011|publisher=SAGE Publications|isbn=978-81-321-0778-1}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Indian women activists]]\n[[Category:People from Thoubal district]]\n[[Category:Community activists]]\n[[Category:Anti-corruption activism in India]]\n[[Category:Indian human rights activists]]\n[[Category:Social movements in India]]\n[[Category:Meitei people]]\n[[Category:History of Manipur]]\n[[Category:Activists from Manipur]]\n[[Category:Women from Manipur]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian women]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Indian English|date=July 2016}}{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}'''Meira Paibi''' (Women torch bearers) is a women's [[social movement]] in the [[States and union territories of India|Indian state]] of [[Manipur]]. Referred to as the \"guardians of civil society\", Meira Paibi dates to 1977 in  present [[Kakching district]]. It derives its name from the flaming torches which the women carry while marching through city streets, often at night. They do so both as a patrol, and in protest, seeking redress against human rights violations committed by paramilitary and armed forces units against the innocent. Contextualized, Meira Paibi was founded at a time when the people of Manipur were fighting for self-determination, political autonomy, and independence. \n\nAccording to ''[[The Times of India]]'', Meira Paibi is the \"largest grassroots, civilian movement fighting state atrocities and human rights violations in Manipur\". One of the movement's leaders, A. K. Janaki Leima, says that \"We've been fighting against drug abuse, crimes against women, and the [[Armed Forces (Special Powers) Act|Armed Forces Special Powers Act]] (AFSPA). We will continue to fight these\".\n\n==Background==\nMeira Paibi was established in 1977 in [[Kakching]], [[Thoubal district]], [[Manipur]], India. Meira Paibis are the women \"guardians of civil society\" and they carry flaming torches and march through city streets, frequently at night doing a patrol duty, and as a way of  protest for seeking redress against human rights violations committed by paramilitary and armed forces units against the innocent. The movement evolved at a time when the people of Manipur were fighting for self-determination, political autonomy, and independence.<ref name=\"Thangjom2013\">{{cite journal|last1=Thangjom|first1=Lalzo S.|title=The Role of MEIRA PAIBI in Bringing about Social Change in the Manipuri Society: An Analysis|journal=Journal of Social Welfare & Management|date=October 2013|volume=5|issue=4|pages=235|url=http://connection.ebscohost.com/c/articles/95644768/role-meira-paibi-bringing-about-social-change-manipuri-society-analysis|accessdate=12 March 2016}}</ref>{{Sfn|Parratt|2005|p=157}}<ref name= Sunil2013>{{Cite web|last= Sunil|first= Oinam|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/TOI-Social-Impact-Awards-Lifetime-contribution-Meira-Paibi/articleshow/17963178.cms|title=TOI Social Impact Awards: Lifetime contribution \u2014 Meira Paibi|date=10 January 2013|accessdate=10 March 2016|newspaper=Times of India}}</ref>\n\n==Predecessor movements==\n===Nupi lan===\n{{main|Nupi lan}}\nWomen's social movements in Manipur date to [[British Raj|British rule]]. Two such movements, collectively known as [[Nupi lan]] (Women's War; Women's Uprising),{{sfn|Thomas|2011|p=168}} preceded Meira Paibi. The first one dates to 1904 when women of the [[Imphal]] valley protested against the [[Assistant Superintendent]] of British authority in Manipur because of his directive to collect teak wood from [[Kabaw Valley|Kabas]] to build his house. The women who protested were neighbors in the locality. British authorities brought forces from outside the state to end this women's protest.{{Sfn|Karna|1998|pp=77\u201380}} A second movement occurred in 1939 as protest to forced rice exportation which was causing starvation among the local people.<ref name= Laithangbam>{{Cite news|last=Laithangbam|first=Iboyaima|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/other-states/women-vigilantes-of-manipur-to-observe-meira-paibi-day-on-december-29/article6563476.ece|title=Women vigilantes of Manipur|date=4 November 2014|newspaper=The Hindu}}</ref> Women, nearly 99% of them, protested peacefully, submitting a petition to the [[Durbar (court)|Durbar]] (government authority). The movement forced closure of rice mills and eventually proved successful in halting the exportation of rice.{{Sfn|Karna|1998|pp=77\u201380}} Nupi Lan became the forerunner in introducing reforms in the state after [[World War II]].<ref name=Yen/> 12 December is observed annually by Meira Paibi as \"Women's War Day\" commemorating the events of 1939.<ref name= Laithangbam/>\n\n===Nisha Bandis===\nThe Nisha Bandis women's movement developed in the late 1970s. Its origins are attributed to [[Meitei people|Meitei]] women's activism combating alcoholism and drug addiction.<ref name= Laithangbam/> The women held night marches in the streets of Imphal and elsewhere in Manipur carrying lanterns, chastising the intoxicated, and setting fire to liquor shops. Their actions lead to the introduction of [[prohibition]] laws in the state.<ref name= Sunil2013/> The late 1970s was a period of civil unrest,<ref name=\"Malindog2014\">{{cite web|last1=Malindog|first1=Anna|title=The Role of Women in Self-Determination Movements|url=http://kashmirwatch.com/the-role-of-women-in-self-determination-movements/|accessdate=12 March 2016|date=2 December 2014}}</ref> which established an underground insurgency movement in Manipur. The [[Armed Forces (Special Powers) Act#Armed Forces Special Powers (Assam and Manipur) Act, 1958|Armed Forces Special Powers Assam and Manipur Act 1958]] permitted paramilitary forces and the police to use unlimited power in dealing with insurgency, resulting in the arrest, torture, and deaths of many innocent young people. The Nisha Bandis became socially active with vigilante activities, protests and marches through the streets of Imphal and elsewhere in the state.{{Sfn|Karna|1998|pp=77\u201380}}<ref name=\"Malindog2014\" />\n\n==Establishment==\n{{Quote box\n | quote  =\"The Manipuri story indicates that active participation by women in public affairs can and does contribute to better conditions for children and society at large\". -[[UNICEF]]<ref name=\"Thangjom2013\" />\n | source =\n | width  =25%\n | align  =right\n}}\nThe Nisha Bandis carried ''podons'' (large-wicked kerosene lamps){{sfn|Thomas|Gopalakrishnan|Singh|2001|p=90}} and ''laltain'' ([[Hindi]], lantern) but after switching to flaming torches, they became known as Meira Paibi.<ref name=\"Nepram2005\">{{cite web|last1=Nepram|first1=Binalakshmi|title=A Narrative on the Origin of the Meira Paibis|url=http://www.e-pao.net/epSubPageExtractor.asp?src=leisure.Essays.A_Narrative_on_the_Origin_of_the_Meira_Paibis|publisher=E-Pao|accessdate=12 March 2016|date=9 January 2005}}</ref> The Meitei women torch bearers represented the declaration of a just war defending [[human rights]] in Manipur.<ref name=Yen>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thesangaiexpress.com/30311-is-the-meira-paibi-movement-facing-extinction/|title=Is the Meira Paibi Movement Facing Extinction?|date=15 September 2013|accessdate=10 March 2016|newspaper=The Sangai ExpRess|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160311191148/http://www.thesangaiexpress.com/30311-is-the-meira-paibi-movement-facing-extinction/|archive-date=11 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> Their movement has expanded to hold \"public meetings, demonstrations, road closures and public bandhs or shut down of all essential services, hunger strikes and mass rallies.\"<ref name=Yen/> These women, also known as \"women vigilantes\", stopped army vehicles, rescued innocent youth who were apprehended on false charges, and negotiated their transfer to the police. The Army did not protest as they respected the role of Meitei women in just causes.<ref name= Laithangbam/> The Meira Paibi's movement has become known as the third Nupi Lan.<ref name=\"Nepram2005\" />\n\n==Recognition==\n''Times of India'' awarded the \"TOI Social Impact Awards: Lifetime contribution\" to Meira Paibi and its five leaders, the 83-year-old Thokchom Ramani, Ak Janaki Leima, L Memchoubi Devi, Y Leirik Leima, and Purnimashi Leima.<ref name= Sunil2013/> These five women  -known as \"imas\" or mothers- take an aggressive posture by lowering their traditional ''phanek'' (floral embroidered Meitei sarong), tie it with a cloth belt (''khwang chet''), and cover their shoulders with the formal ''phi'' (embroidered phanek). They also tie a piece of cloth over their head in the form of a [[turban]]. They carry the flaming torch as a symbol of their feminist movement supporting human rights and peace.<ref name= Sunil2013/>\n''Uday '' awarded the\n''Struggle of Meira Paibi''\nTheir fought for the struggle using torch. Many named it with many names but it was Meira Paibi's Movement.\n\n<br />\n\n== Film on Meira Paibi ==\nA short documentary film on Meira Paibi was made in 2018. The film titled, Fireflies is directed by Johnson Rajkumar.<ref>{{Citation|title=Fireflies 2018|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt8011806/|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref>The film focuses on an underrated women\u2019s social movement active in Manipur. Appreciated both by movie buffs and critics, the 6-minute documentary explores the role of women in the conflict-ridden, male-dominated society of Manipur.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eclecticnortheast.in/2018/04/manipuri-activist-makes-documentary-meira-paibis/|title=Manipuri Activist Makes Documentary on Meira Paibis|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>The film articulates the journey of Meira Paibi, a women\u2019s social movement in Manipur, in their struggles to protect the community from atrocities committed by the state.Through powerful testimonies, the film looks into how gender identities are negotiated during times of conflict and violence. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eastmojo.com/manipur/2019/12/20/manipuri-documentary-fireflies-screened-at-kathmandu-film-fest|title=Manipuri documentary \u2018Fireflies\u2019 screened at Kathmandu film fest|last=EastMojo|first=Team|website=EastMojo|language=en|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref>\n\nThe film has got both national and international appreciation. The film had won Best Short Documentary in Arthouse Asia International Film Festival, Kolkata and won second place in short documentary section in Chennai International Short Film Festival.The film had also been selected in several international and national film festivals including Golden Tree International Documentary Film Festival in Frankfurt, Dada Saheb Phalke International Film Festival in Mumbai, Davis Feminist Film Festival in California and Human Rights Short Film Festival in Dhaka, Bangladesh<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eastmojo.com/manipur/2019/12/20/manipuri-documentary-fireflies-screened-at-kathmandu-film-fest|title=Manipuri documentary \u2018Fireflies\u2019 screened at Kathmandu film fest|last=EastMojo|first=Team|website=EastMojo|language=en|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref>\n\nThe trailer is available here: [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HoeoEOb6p0s&t=2s Fireflies Trailer]\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Ima Market]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Karna|first=Mahendra Narain|title=Social Movements in North-East India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-3FJEfU3swcC&pg=PA77|year=1998|publisher=Indus Publishing|isbn=978-81-7387-083-5}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Parratt|first=John|title=Wounded Land: Politics and Identity in Modern Manipur|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fO4N_FI8jt4C&pg=PA157|year=2005|publisher=Mittal Publications|isbn=978-81-8324-053-6}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last1=Thomas|first1=C. Joshua|last2=Gopalakrishnan|first2=Ramamoorthy|last3=Singh|first3=R. K. Ranjan|title=Constraints In Development Of Manipur|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AFxuAAAAMAAJ|year= 2001|publisher=Regency Publications &#91;for Policy Alternatives for the North-East and Conflict Elimination Awareness&#93;|isbn=978-81-87498-30-8}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Thomas|first=Pradip Ninan|title=Negotiating Communication Rights: Case Studies from India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=W9yGAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA168|year=2011|publisher=SAGE Publications|isbn=978-81-321-0778-1}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Indian women activists]]\n[[Category:People from Thoubal district]]\n[[Category:Community activists]]\n[[Category:Anti-corruption activism in India]]\n[[Category:Indian human rights activists]]\n[[Category:Social movements in India]]\n[[Category:Meitei people]]\n[[Category:History of Manipur]]\n[[Category:Activists from Manipur]]\n[[Category:Women from Manipur]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian women]]\n", "name_user": "Manipurhistory", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meira_Paibi"}
{"title_page": "Zenos Frudakis", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist\n| name          = Zenos Frudakis\n| image         = Benjamin Franklin Zenos Frudakis.jpg\n| caption       = Zenos Frudakis working on his sculpture of Benjamin Franklin\n| birth_name     = \n| birth_date     = {{birth year and age|1951}}\n| birth_place   = [[San Francisco]], [[California]], [[United States]]\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| nationality   = [[American nationality law|American]]\n| field         = [[Sculpture]]\n| training      = [[Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts]];  [[University of Pennsylvania]]\n| movement      = \n| works  = ''Freedom Sculpture'', ''[[United States Air Force Memorial]] Honor Guard'', ''Knowledge is Power'', ''Payne Stewart'' at Pinehurst Golf Course\n}}\n'''Zenos Frudakis''' (born 1951) is an American [[sculptors|sculptor]] whose subjects include portraits of living and historical individuals and poetic/philosophical sculpture. He lives and works near [[Philadelphia]]. His works include those at [[Brookgreen Gardens]],<ref>Robin R. Salmon, ''Brookgreen Gardens Sculpture'' (Brookgreen Gardens, 1993), v. 2, pp. 188-91.</ref> the [[Lotos Club]] of New York City,<ref name=\"The Lotos Experience 1995 pp. 34-35\">''The Lotos Experience, The Tradition Continues'' (Lotos Club, 1995), pp. 34-35.</ref> the Utsukushi ga-hara Open Air Museum in [[Japan]],<ref>''Third Rodin Grand Prize Exhibit, The Utsukushi-ga-hara Open Air Museum,'' Hakone Open Air Museum, Embassies of Greece, Spain, United Kingdom and British Consul, United States, West Germany, 1990, pp. 27-28.</ref> the [[National Academy of Design]],<ref>When an artist is voted into membership in the National Academy the Academy accepts a work of art from that artist; Frudakis's work was ''Sheila'', a life-size bronze bust.</ref> and the [[U.S. Embassy]] in [[Pretoria]], [[South Africa]]<ref>Gene Freedman, \"The Unveiling of a Memorial,\" ''USIA World'', April 1989, pp. 10-11. See also \"Hope and Glory,\" ''Philadelphia Inquirer'', Sunday March 12, 1989, cover and pp. 4H-5H; \"Martin Luther King Jr Is Remembered,\" ''Herald International Tribune'', January 17, 1989, front page; and \"Bust of Dr. King,\" ''Washington Post'', January 17, 1989, p. 1.</ref>\n[[File:Freedom Zenos Frudakis.jpg|thumb|650px|left|The Freedom Sculpture with sculptor Zenos Frudakis]]\n[[File:Martin Luther King and Freedom sculpture.jpg|thumb|Martin Luther King and Freedom sculpture]]\n[[File:Reaching sculpture with Zenos Frudakis. Utsukushi-ga-hara Open Air Museum, Japan.jpg|thumb|Reaching sculpture with Zenos Frudakis at the Utsukushi-ga-hara Open Air Museum in Japan.]]\n\n\n\n== Biography ==\nZenos' father, born in [[Greece]], came to the U.S. as a boy. The oldest of five children growing up in Greek culture, Zenos admired, respected, and was drawn to Greek sculpture. Greek art influenced his aesthetic vision; additional inspiration came from sculptors [[Michelangelo]], [[Gian Lorenzo Bernini|Bernini]], [[Jean-Baptiste Carpeaux|Carpeaux]] and [[Auguste Rodin|Rodin]]. The poetry of [[T. S. Eliot|Eliot]], [[Robert Frost|Frost]], [[Theodore Roethke|Roethke]] and [[Robert Graves|Graves]], is important to Zenos, as is philosophy.\n\n\nBorn in 1951 in [[San Francisco]], Frudakis was raised in [[Wheeling, West Virginia]], and [[Gary, Indiana]], where he worked in the steel mills. He began drawing at a very young age, and in 1972 came to Philadelphia to study at the [[Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts]]. He studied sculpture with two [[Prix de Rome]] winners: his elder brother, sculptor Evangelos Frudakis, and painter James Hanes. At the [[University of Pennsylvania]], he earned bachelor's and master's degrees in Fine Art.<ref>Sarah Blackman, \"Sculpting a Life\" (feature article on Frudakis), ''The Pennsylvania Gazette'', Class of '82, November/December 2002, p. 3.</ref>\n\n\n==International Sculptures==\n* ''[[Reaching (sculpture)|Reaching]]''. Two figures (bronze | 7ft) Utsukushi-ga-hara Open Air Museum, [[Japan]]. 3rd Rodin Grand Prize Exhibition, July 20, 1990.<ref>Henry, Jean \"Contemporary Figurative Sculpture,\" ''The National Sculpture Society Celebrates the Figure'' (National Sculpture Society, 1987), pp. 52-53.</ref><ref>{{Cite web| author= The Hakone Open-Air Museum | url=https://static1.squarespace.com/static/53f662b0e4b083b394ab3f14/t/55110825e4b03d839644c042/1427179557796/19900124.Reaching.HakoneLetter.jpg | title= \u201cLetter to Zenos Frudakis\u201d |accessdate=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n* ''[[Honor Guard]]''. Memorial (bronze | 16ft) Imperial War Museum, Duxford, [[England]]. Dedication 2018.<ref>Imperial War Museum. \u201cMemorial Honor Guard\u201d IWM, Duxford, Cambridgeshire, England.</ref>\n* ''Martin Luther King and Freedom''. Public sculpture (bronze) Peace Garden, University of New South Wales, [[Sydney, Australia]]. Dedication October 19, 2018.<ref>Mavros, Larissa, University of New South Wales, Sydney Newsroom, \u201cBust of Dr. Martin Luther King Jr Joins Gallery of Human Rights Icons at UNSW Sydney\u201d October 19, 2018. Sydney, Australia. </ref>\n* ''[[Lois Browne-Evans|Hon. Dame Lois Browne-Evans]]. Statue (bronze | life-size) Justice Center, Dame Lois Browne Evans Building (Police/Justice Center) [[Hamilton, Bermuda]]. Dedication June 2011.<ref>Aarabdhekivuc, Nadia, The Royal Gazette, \u201cNew Police, Court Building Formally Opened\u201d June 13, 2011. Bermuda. Retrieved 2020-03-29.</ref> \n* ''[[Arnold Palmer]]''. Statue (bronze | over-life-size) Tralee Golf Club, Tralee, County Kerry, [[Ireland]]. Dedication September 10, 2007.<ref>Mavros, Larissa, University of New South Wales, Sydney Newsroom, \u201cBust of Dr. Martin Luther King Jr Joins Gallery of Human Rights Icons at UNSW Sydney\u201d October 19, 2018. Sydney, Australia.</ref>\n* ''[[Constantine Papadakis|Dr. Constantine Papadakis]]''. Drexel University President, Portrait bust (bronze | life size) Town Square, Meskla, [[Greece]]. Dedication July 24, 2010.<ref>DrexelNow, \u201cTown Square in Greece to be Named for Late Drexel President Papadakis\u201d Drexel University, Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, July 20, 2010.</ref>\n* ''Lamby (Abigail), Irish Wolfhound''. Bronze (life-size | 12ft x 11ft) Old Bladbean Stud Garden, Canterbury, [[Kent, England]].<ref>Harpur, Marcus, Country Life \u201cWhere Art Imitates Life\u201d p.44-48, UK, August 5, 2015.</ref>\n\n[[File:Payne Stewart by Zenos Frudakis.jpg|thumb|Payne Stewart sculpture at Pinehust by Zenos Frudakis.]]\n[[File:Knowledge is Power.jpg|thumb|Knowledge is Power.]]\n\n\n\n==American Sculptures==\nIn a career spanning over four decades, Frudakis has produced monumental figures such as the [[United States Air Force Memorial]] ''Honor Guard''<ref name=air-force_memorial>Col. Walter Boyne, ''Soaring to Glory, The United States Air Force Memorial'' (for the Air Force Memorial Foundation by the Donning Company, 2007), Chapter 7, \"A Perfect Partnership,\" pp. 80-93. See also \"Guard Honored,\" ''The Academy Spirit'', United States Air Force Academy, Colorado, v. 47, no. 40 (October 5, 2007), p. 1.</ref> installed at the Arlington National Cemetery, and ''Freedom in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.<ref>''Art Business News'', September 2001, front page photograph.</ref>\n\n\n===Monumental Sculptures===\n* ''Freedom Sculpture''. Monument (Bronze | 20ft x 8ft | 7,000lbs) 16th and Vine Streets, [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]]. Completed 2000. Dedication June 18, 2001.<ref>Sculpture Review, ''\u201cChanging the American Landscape,\u201d'' Fall 2001, Vol.L, No.3, p.32, [[National Sculpture Society]], [[New York, New York]].</ref>\n* ''[[Honor Guard|U.S. Air Force Memorial Honor Guard]]''. Memorial (Bronze | Monument) [[Arlington National Cemetery]], [[Arlington, Virginia]]. Dedication: October 14, 2006.<ref>{{Cite web| author= Air Force District of Washington.  | url=https://www.afdw.af.mil/heritage/ | title= \u201cAir Force Memorial\u201d |accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n* ''Knowledge is Power''. Monument (Bronze | 8ft x 15ft | 1,500lbs) Over 30 portraits from intellectual history, two 8ft figures free standing. Relief wall portraits: [[Harriet Tubman]], [[Martin Luther King Jr.]], [[Rachel Carson]], [[Harriet Beecher Stowe]], [[Darwin]], [[Albert Einstein]], [[Alan Turing]], [[John Muir]], [[Thoreau]], [[James Hall]]. [[Rowan University]], [[Glassboro, New Jersey]]. Dedication Nov. 21, 2014.<ref>{{Cite web| author= Rowan University Libraries, Public Art.  | url=https://publicart.rowan.edu/sculptures/knowledge-is-power-2014/ | title= \u201cKnowledge Is Power\u201d |accessdate=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n* ''Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr.'', Monument (Bronze portrait bust, granite base / 5ft / 685lbs) Martin Luther King Park, J. Lewis Crozer Library, Chester, Pennsylvania. Dedication November 23, 2010. <ref>{{Cite web| author= Chester City, Chester\u2019s Park System.  | url=https://www.chestercity.com/departments/parks-recreation/chesters-park-system/ | title= Martin Luther King Park |accessdate=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n* ''The Path to Manhood'', Monument (Bronze | Over-life-size) Perot Quadrangle, [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/St._Mark%27s_School_of_Texas  St. Mark\u2019s School of Texas], [[Dallas, Texas]]. <ref>{{Cite web| author= St. Mark\u2019s School of Texas, David W. Dini, Headmaster. | url=https://www.smtexas.org/2016-2017/hmremarks | title= Remarks from the Headmaster |accessdate=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n\n===Memorials===\n* ''[[Honor Guard|U.S. Air Force Memorial Honor Guard]]''. Memorial (Bronze | Monument) [[Arlington National Cemetery]], [[Arlington, Virginia]]. Dedication: October 14, 2006.<ref>{{Cite web| author= Air Force District of Washington.  | url=https://www.afdw.af.mil/heritage/ | title= \u201cAir Force Memorial\u201d |accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n* ''[[Molly Maguires]] Memorial'' (Bronze | larger-than-life) Molly Maguires Memorial Park, [[Mahanoy City, Pennsylvania]]. Dedication: June 21, 2002<ref>{{Cite web| author= Kelly, Joseph Dennis  | url=https://irishamerica.com/2002/02/the-molly-maguires-remembered/ | title= \u201cThe Molly Maguires Remembered\u201d |accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n* ''The Workers\u2019 Memorial'' (Bronze | 8ft figure, Mayari-r Steel circle, granite base | 2,500 lbs) The Rose Garden, [[Bethlehem, Pennsylvania]]. Sponsored by 20 unions, 15 non-union industries, 3 cities: Allentown, Bethlehem, Easton Pennsylvania. Dedication: April 28, 1991 <ref>{{Cite web| author= Devlin, Ron, The Morning Call. | url=https://www.mcall.com/news/mc-xpm-1991-04-28-2802053-story.html | title= \u201cSculpture a Memorial to Workers\u201d |accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n* ''Anthracite Miners\u2019 Memorial''. Relief (Bronze | Left and right panels 6 x 4ft, central panel 8ft sq). Giard Park, [[Shenandoah, Pennsylvania]]. Dedication: 1996<ref>{{Cite web| author=The Historical Marker Database | url= https://www.hmdb.org/m.asp?m=86761 | title=Pennsylvania Athracite Miners Memorial |accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n* ''[[Nina Simone]]''. Memorial (Bronze, local stone | 8ft figure) Nina Simone Plaza, [[Tryon, North Carolina]]. Dedication: February 21, 2010.<ref>{{Cite web| author= UNC Libraries, Commemorative Landscapes of North Carolina. | url=https://ncpedia.org/monument/nina-simone-sculpture | title= \u201cNina Simone Sculpture\u201d |accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n* ''[[Constantine Papadakis | Dr. Constantine \u2018Taki\u2019 Papadakis]].'' Memorial (Bronze | life size). Public Square in Meskla, [[Greece]]. Dedication: July 24, 2010<ref>{{Cite web| author= Drexel University | url =https://drexel.edu/now/archive/2010/July/Town-Square-in-Greece-to-be-Named-for-Late-Drexel-President-Papadakis/ | title=Town Square in Greece to be Named for Late Drexel President Papadakis\n |accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n* ''Henry L. Bowden''. Memorial (Bronze bas-relief | over-life-size). Henry L. Bowden Hall, [[Emory University]], [[Atlanta, Georgia]]. Dedication: 1991<ref>{{Cite web| author= Emory University | url =http://www.emoryhistory.emory.edu/facts-figures/places/names/atlanta/bowden-hall.html | title=Henry L. Bowden Hall |accessdate=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* ''Mr. and Mrs Hillenbrand''. Memorial (Bronze bas-relief | life size). Batesville Memorial Public Library, [[Batesville, Indiana]]. Dedication: 1988.\n* ''Veterans Memorial''. Memorial (Bronze | over-life-size). Henry L. Bowden Hall, [[Emory University]], [[Collegeville, Pennsylvania]]. Dedication: 1991\n\n\n===Portrait Statues===\n* ''[[Payne Stewart]]''. Bronze, over-life-size sculpture. [[Pinehurst Resort]], [[Pinehurst, North Carolina|Pinehurst]], North Carolina.<ref>Lee Pace, ''The Spirit of Pinehurst'' (Pinehurst Resort, 2007), pp. 86-87. See also ''World Golf Courses'' (Chartwell Books, 2007), pp. 144-45.</ref>\n*''[[Clarence Darrow]]''. Bronze, over-life-size, the [[Rhea County Courthouse]], [[Dayton, Tennessee|Dayton]], Tennessee.\n*''[[Frederick Law Olmsted]]''. Bronze, over-life-size, The [[North Carolina Arboretum]], [[Asheville, North Carolina|Asheville]], North Carolina.\n\n\n===Portrait Busts===\n* ''[[Mark Twain]]''. Bronze, over-life-size sculpture. The Lotos Club, [[New York City|New York]], New York.<ref>\"The Lotos Experience 1995 pp. 34-35\"</ref>\n\n\n\n==Awards==\nFrudakis is a member of the prestigious [[National Sculpture Society]].<ref name=nss_fellow>{{Cite web| author=National Sculpture Society| url=https://nationalsculpture.org/author/zenos_frudakis/| title= Fellows of NSS |accessdate=2012-03-30}}</ref>\n\nIn 1990, Frudakis was invited to participate in Japan's Third Rodin Grand Prize Exhibition, where he won the Hakone Award at Utsukushi-ga-hara Open Air Museum.<ref>Third Rodin Grand Prize Exhibit, The Utsukushi-ga-hara Open Air Museum, Hakone Open Air Museum, Embassies of Greece, Spain, United Kingdom and British Consul, United States, West Germany, 1990, pp. 27-28.</ref> The Museum purchased a cast of Frudakis's sculpture ''Reaching''.<ref>Donald Reynolds, ''Masters of American Sculpture'' (Abbeville Press, 1993), p. 250.</ref>\n\nIn 1991 he was elected into the [[National Academy of Design]] as an Associate member, and became a full Academician in 1993.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"200\">\n<!-- Deleted image removed: Image:Zenos_Frudakis_Dream_To_Fly_Cherry_Hill.jpg|Dream to Fly, Cherry Hill, NJ -->\nImage:Zenos_Frudakis_Gateway_to_Growth_in_progress.JPG|Gateway to Growth (in progress)\nImage:Chef Pep\u00edn, portrait sculpture and sculptor Zenos Frudakis.jpg|Chef Pepin, portrait sculpture and Frudakis\nImage:Zenos_Frudakis_General_Yarborough_Fayetteville.JPG|General Yarborough, Airborne & Special Ops Museum, Fayetteville, NC\nImage:Zenos_Frudakis_Jack_Nicklaus_Louisville.jpg|[[Jack Nicklaus]], Dwight Gahm [[Valhalla Golf Club]], Louisville, KY\nImage:Dwight Eisenhower sculpture by Zenos Frudakis.jpg|thumb|Portrait sculpture of Dwight D. Eisenhower by Zenos Frudakis.\nImage:Zenos_Frudakis_Mark_Twain_Lotos.jpg|[[Mark Twain]], The [[Lotos Club]], New York, NY\nImage:Nina Simone Statue Tryon, North Carolina.jpg|[[Nina Simone]] in [[Tryon, North Carolina]]<ref name=\"Simone_Malone\">{{cite news |last1=MALONE |first1=GINA |title=Funds sought to pay off Nina Simone statue |url=http://www.goupstate.com/article/NC/20130717/Entertainment/605138687/SJ/ |work=GoUpstate |agency=GATEHOUSE MEDIA, LLC. |publisher=Halifax Media Group |date=17 July 2013 |language=en}}</ref>\nImage:Zenos_Frudakis_Mike_Schmidt_Philadelphia.jpg|[[Mike Schmidt]], [[Citizens Bank Park]], Philadelphia, PA<ref name=mike_schmidt>{{Cite web|author=Citizens Bank Park|url=http://www.ballparkreviews.com/philly/cit.htm#|title=Citizens Bank Park|accessdate=2012-03-30}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Carchidi|first=Sam|year=2004|title=Four legends honored with statues|periodical=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]|issue=April 13|pages=F8}}</ref>\nImage:Zenos Frudakis Arnold Palmer Legioner.jpg|thumb|[[Arnold Palmer]]\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Appelbaum, David, and Mel Thompson, editors. ''World Philosophy''. Vega, 2002, pp.&nbsp;250\u201351.\n* Boyne, Walter J., Rosalie Frudakis, Katherine Jaeger, et al. ''The United States Air Force Memorial Honor Guard, A Sculpture by Zenos Frudakis''. Techni Press, 2007.\n* Dunhoff, Richard, and Philip H. Wagner. ''Philadelphia, A Photographic Portrait.'' Twin Lights Publishers, 2004, p.&nbsp;14.\n* Goode, James M. ''Washington Sculpture.'' Johns Hopkins University Press, 2008.\n* Gordon, Robert, and Tom Burgoyne. ''Movin' On Up''. MidAtlantic Press, 2004, pp.&nbsp;264\u201364.\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.zenosfrudakis.com}}\n* [https://www.facebook.com/ZenosFrudakis Zenos Frudakis: Facebook]\n* [https://twitter.com/ZenosFrudakis Zenos Frudakis: Twitter]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Frudakis, Zenos}}\n[[Category:American sculptors]]\n[[Category:Sculptors from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:American people of Greek descent]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:Artists from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:People from Wheeling, West Virginia]]\n[[Category:People from Gary, Indiana]]\n[[Category:Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Pennsylvania School of Design alumni]]\n[[Category:Sculptors from California]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artist\n| name          = Zenos Frudakis\n| image         = Benjamin Franklin Zenos Frudakis.jpg\n| caption       = Zenos Frudakis working on his sculpture of Benjamin Franklin\n| birth_name     = \n| birth_date     = {{birth year and age|1951}}\n| birth_place   = [[San Francisco]], [[California]], [[United States]]\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| nationality   = [[American nationality law|American]]\n| field         = [[Sculpture]]\n| training      = [[Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts]];  [[University of Pennsylvania]]\n| movement      = \n| works  = ''Freedom Sculpture'', ''[[United States Air Force Memorial]] Honor Guard'', ''Knowledge is Power'', ''Payne Stewart'' at Pinehurst Golf Course\n}}\n'''Zenos Frudakis''' (born 1951) is an American [[sculptors|sculptor]] whose subjects include portraits of living and historical individuals and poetic/philosophical sculpture. He lives and works near [[Philadelphia]]. His works include those at [[Brookgreen Gardens]],<ref>Robin R. Salmon, ''Brookgreen Gardens Sculpture'' (Brookgreen Gardens, 1993), v. 2, pp. 188-91.</ref> the [[Lotos Club]] of New York City,<ref name=\"The Lotos Experience 1995 pp. 34-35\">''The Lotos Experience, The Tradition Continues'' (Lotos Club, 1995), pp. 34-35.</ref> the Utsukushi ga-hara Open Air Museum in [[Japan]],<ref>''Third Rodin Grand Prize Exhibit, The Utsukushi-ga-hara Open Air Museum,'' Hakone Open Air Museum, Embassies of Greece, Spain, United Kingdom and British Consul, United States, West Germany, 1990, pp. 27-28.</ref> the [[National Academy of Design]],<ref>When an artist is voted into membership in the National Academy the Academy accepts a work of art from that artist; Frudakis's work was ''Sheila'', a life-size bronze bust.</ref> and the [[U.S. Embassy]] in [[Pretoria]], [[South Africa]]<ref>Gene Freedman, \"The Unveiling of a Memorial,\" ''USIA World'', April 1989, pp. 10-11. See also \"Hope and Glory,\" ''Philadelphia Inquirer'', Sunday March 12, 1989, cover and pp. 4H-5H; \"Martin Luther King Jr Is Remembered,\" ''Herald International Tribune'', January 17, 1989, front page; and \"Bust of Dr. King,\" ''Washington Post'', January 17, 1989, p. 1.</ref>\n[[File:Freedom Zenos Frudakis.jpg|thumb|650px|left|The Freedom Sculpture with sculptor Zenos Frudakis]]\n[[File:Martin Luther King and Freedom sculpture.jpg|thumb|Martin Luther King and Freedom sculpture]]\n[[File:Reaching sculpture with Zenos Frudakis. Utsukushi-ga-hara Open Air Museum, Japan.jpg|thumb|Reaching sculpture with Zenos Frudakis at the Utsukushi-ga-hara Open Air Museum in Japan.]]\n\n\n\n== Biography ==\nZenos' father, born in [[Greece]], came to the U.S. as a boy. The oldest of five children growing up in Greek culture, Zenos admired, respected, and was drawn to Greek sculpture. Greek art influenced his aesthetic vision; additional inspiration came from sculptors [[Michelangelo]], [[Gian Lorenzo Bernini|Bernini]], [[Jean-Baptiste Carpeaux|Carpeaux]] and [[Auguste Rodin|Rodin]]. The poetry of [[T. S. Eliot|Eliot]], [[Robert Frost|Frost]], [[Theodore Roethke|Roethke]] and [[Robert Graves|Graves]], is important to Zenos, as is philosophy.\n\n\nBorn in 1951 in [[San Francisco]], Frudakis was raised in [[Wheeling, West Virginia]], and [[Gary, Indiana]], where he worked in the steel mills. He began drawing at a very young age, and in 1972 came to Philadelphia to study at the [[Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts]]. He studied sculpture with two [[Prix de Rome]] winners: his elder brother, sculptor Evangelos Frudakis, and painter James Hanes. At the [[University of Pennsylvania]], he earned bachelor's and master's degrees in Fine Art.<ref>Sarah Blackman, \"Sculpting a Life\" (feature article on Frudakis), ''The Pennsylvania Gazette'', Class of '82, November/December 2002, p. 3.</ref>\n\n\n==International Sculptures==\n* ''[[Reaching (sculpture)|Reaching]]''. Two figures (bronze | 7ft) Utsukushi-ga-hara Open Air Museum, [[Japan]]. 3rd Rodin Grand Prize Exhibition, July 20, 1990.<ref>Henry, Jean \"Contemporary Figurative Sculpture,\" ''The National Sculpture Society Celebrates the Figure'' (National Sculpture Society, 1987), pp. 52-53.</ref><ref>{{Cite web| author= The Hakone Open-Air Museum | url=https://static1.squarespace.com/static/53f662b0e4b083b394ab3f14/t/55110825e4b03d839644c042/1427179557796/19900124.Reaching.HakoneLetter.jpg | title= \u201cLetter to Zenos Frudakis\u201d |accessdate=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n* ''[[Honor Guard]]''. Memorial (bronze | 16ft) Imperial War Museum, Duxford, [[England]]. Dedication 2018.<ref>Imperial War Museum. \u201cMemorial Honor Guard\u201d IWM, Duxford, Cambridgeshire, England.</ref>\n* ''Martin Luther King and Freedom''. Public sculpture (bronze) Peace Garden, University of New South Wales, [[Sydney, Australia]]. Dedication October 19, 2018.<ref>Mavros, Larissa, University of New South Wales, Sydney Newsroom, \u201cBust of Dr. Martin Luther King Jr Joins Gallery of Human Rights Icons at UNSW Sydney\u201d October 19, 2018. Sydney, Australia. </ref>\n* ''[[Lois Browne-Evans|Hon. Dame Lois Browne-Evans]]. Statue (bronze | life-size) Justice Center, Dame Lois Browne Evans Building (Police/Justice Center) [[Hamilton, Bermuda]]. Dedication June 2011.<ref>Aarabdhekivuc, Nadia, The Royal Gazette, \u201cNew Police, Court Building Formally Opened\u201d June 13, 2011. Bermuda. Retrieved 2020-03-29.</ref> \n* ''[[Arnold Palmer]]''. Statue (bronze | over-life-size) Tralee Golf Club, Tralee, County Kerry, [[Ireland]]. Dedication September 10, 2007.<ref>Mavros, Larissa, University of New South Wales, Sydney Newsroom, \u201cBust of Dr. Martin Luther King Jr Joins Gallery of Human Rights Icons at UNSW Sydney\u201d October 19, 2018. Sydney, Australia.</ref>\n* ''[[Constantine Papadakis|Dr. Constantine Papadakis]]''. Drexel University President, Portrait bust (bronze | life size) Town Square, Meskla, [[Greece]]. Dedication July 24, 2010.<ref>DrexelNow, \u201cTown Square in Greece to be Named for Late Drexel President Papadakis\u201d Drexel University, Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, July 20, 2010.</ref>\n* ''Lamby (Abigail), Irish Wolfhound''. Bronze (life-size | 12ft x 11ft) Old Bladbean Stud Garden, Canterbury, [[Kent, England]].<ref>Harpur, Marcus, Country Life \u201cWhere Art Imitates Life\u201d p.44-48, UK, August 5, 2015.</ref>\n\n[[File:Payne Stewart by Zenos Frudakis.jpg|thumb|Payne Stewart sculpture at Pinehust by Zenos Frudakis.]]\n[[File:Knowledge is Power.jpg|thumb|Knowledge is Power.]]\n\n\n\n==American Sculptures==\nIn a career spanning over four decades, Frudakis has produced monumental figures such as the [[United States Air Force Memorial]] ''Honor Guard''<ref name=air-force_memorial>Col. Walter Boyne, ''Soaring to Glory, The United States Air Force Memorial'' (for the Air Force Memorial Foundation by the Donning Company, 2007), Chapter 7, \"A Perfect Partnership,\" pp. 80-93. See also \"Guard Honored,\" ''The Academy Spirit'', United States Air Force Academy, Colorado, v. 47, no. 40 (October 5, 2007), p. 1.</ref> installed at the Arlington National Cemetery, and ''Freedom in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.<ref>''Art Business News'', September 2001, front page photograph.</ref>\n\n\n===Monumental Sculptures===\n* ''Freedom Sculpture''. Monument (Bronze | 20ft x 8ft | 7,000lbs) 16th and Vine Streets, [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]]. Completed 2000. Dedication June 18, 2001.<ref>Sculpture Review, ''\u201cChanging the American Landscape,\u201d'' Fall 2001, Vol.L, No.3, p.32, [[National Sculpture Society]], [[New York, New York]].</ref>\n* ''[[Honor Guard|U.S. Air Force Memorial Honor Guard]]''. Memorial (Bronze | Monument) [[Arlington National Cemetery]], [[Arlington, Virginia]]. Dedication: October 14, 2006.<ref>{{Cite web| author= Air Force District of Washington.  | url=https://www.afdw.af.mil/heritage/ | title= \u201cAir Force Memorial\u201d |accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n* ''Knowledge is Power''. Monument (Bronze | 8ft x 15ft | 1,500lbs) Over 30 portraits from intellectual history, two 8ft figures free standing. Relief wall portraits: [[Harriet Tubman]], [[Martin Luther King Jr.]], [[Rachel Carson]], [[Harriet Beecher Stowe]], [[Darwin]], [[Albert Einstein]], [[Alan Turing]], [[John Muir]], [[Thoreau]], [[James Hall]]. [[Rowan University]], [[Glassboro, New Jersey]]. Dedication Nov. 21, 2014.<ref>{{Cite web| author= Rowan University Libraries, Public Art.  | url=https://publicart.rowan.edu/sculptures/knowledge-is-power-2014/ | title= \u201cKnowledge Is Power\u201d |accessdate=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n* ''Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr.'', Monument (Bronze portrait bust, granite base / 5ft / 685lbs) Martin Luther King Park, J. Lewis Crozer Library, Chester, Pennsylvania. Dedication November 23, 2010. <ref>{{Cite web| author= Chester City, Chester\u2019s Park System.  | url=https://www.chestercity.com/departments/parks-recreation/chesters-park-system/ | title= Martin Luther King Park |accessdate=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n* ''The Path to Manhood'', Monument (Bronze | Over-life-size) Perot Quadrangle, [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/St._Mark%27s_School_of_Texas  St. Mark\u2019s School of Texas], [[Dallas, Texas]]. <ref>{{Cite web| author= St. Mark\u2019s School of Texas, David W. Dini, Headmaster. | url=https://www.smtexas.org/2016-2017/hmremarks | title= Remarks from the Headmaster |accessdate=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n\n===Memorials===\n* ''[[Honor Guard|U.S. Air Force Memorial Honor Guard]]''. Memorial (Bronze | Monument) [[Arlington National Cemetery]], [[Arlington, Virginia]]. Dedication: October 14, 2006.<ref>{{Cite web| author= Air Force District of Washington.  | url=https://www.afdw.af.mil/heritage/ | title= \u201cAir Force Memorial\u201d |accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n* ''[[Molly Maguires]] Memorial'' (Bronze | larger-than-life) Molly Maguires Memorial Park, [[Mahanoy City, Pennsylvania]]. Dedication: June 21, 2002<ref>{{Cite web| author= Kelly, Joseph Dennis  | url=https://irishamerica.com/2002/02/the-molly-maguires-remembered/ | title= \u201cThe Molly Maguires Remembered\u201d |accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n* ''The Workers\u2019 Memorial'' (Bronze | 8ft figure, Mayari-r Steel circle, granite base | 2,500 lbs) The Rose Garden, [[Bethlehem, Pennsylvania]]. Sponsored by 20 unions, 15 non-union industries, 3 cities: Allentown, Bethlehem, Easton Pennsylvania. Dedication: April 28, 1991 <ref>{{Cite web| author= Devlin, Ron, The Morning Call. | url=https://www.mcall.com/news/mc-xpm-1991-04-28-2802053-story.html | title= \u201cSculpture a Memorial to Workers\u201d |accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n* ''Anthracite Miners\u2019 Memorial''. Relief (Bronze | Left and right panels 6 x 4ft, central panel 8ft sq). Giard Park, [[Shenandoah, Pennsylvania]]. Dedication: 1996<ref>{{Cite web| author=The Historical Marker Database | url= https://www.hmdb.org/m.asp?m=86761 | title=Pennsylvania Athracite Miners Memorial |accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n* ''[[Nina Simone]]''. Memorial (Bronze, local stone | 8ft figure) Nina Simone Plaza, [[Tryon, North Carolina]]. Dedication: February 21, 2010.<ref>{{Cite web| author= UNC Libraries, Commemorative Landscapes of North Carolina. | url=https://ncpedia.org/monument/nina-simone-sculpture | title= \u201cNina Simone Sculpture\u201d |accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n* ''[[Constantine Papadakis | Dr. Constantine \u2018Taki\u2019 Papadakis]].'' Memorial (Bronze | life size). Public Square in Meskla, [[Greece]]. Dedication: July 24, 2010<ref>{{Cite web| author= Drexel University | url =https://drexel.edu/now/archive/2010/July/Town-Square-in-Greece-to-be-Named-for-Late-Drexel-President-Papadakis/ | title=Town Square in Greece to be Named for Late Drexel President Papadakis\n |accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n* ''Henry L. Bowden''. Memorial (Bronze bas-relief | over-life-size). Henry L. Bowden Hall, [[Emory University]], [[Atlanta, Georgia]]. Dedication: 1991<ref>{{Cite web| author= Emory University | url =http://www.emoryhistory.emory.edu/facts-figures/places/names/atlanta/bowden-hall.html | title=Henry L. Bowden Hall |accessdate=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* ''Mr. and Mrs Hillenbrand''. Memorial (Bronze bas-relief | life size). Batesville Memorial Public Library, [[Batesville, Indiana]]. Dedication: 1988.\n* ''Veterans Memorial''. Memorial (Bronze | over-life-size). Henry L. Bowden Hall, [[Emory University]], [[Collegeville, Pennsylvania]]. Dedication: 1991\n\n===Portrait Statues===\n* ''[[Payne Stewart]]''. Bronze, over-life-size sculpture. [[Pinehurst Resort]], [[Pinehurst, North Carolina|Pinehurst]], North Carolina.<ref>Lee Pace, ''The Spirit of Pinehurst'' (Pinehurst Resort, 2007), pp. 86-87. See also ''World Golf Courses'' (Chartwell Books, 2007), pp. 144-45.</ref>\n*''[[Clarence Darrow]]''. Bronze, over-life-size, the [[Rhea County Courthouse]], [[Dayton, Tennessee|Dayton]], Tennessee.\n*''[[Frederick Law Olmsted]]''. Bronze, over-life-size, The [[North Carolina Arboretum]], [[Asheville, North Carolina|Asheville]], North Carolina.\n\n\n===Portrait Busts===\n* ''[[Mark Twain]]''. Bronze, over-life-size sculpture. The Lotos Club, [[New York City|New York]], New York.<ref>\"The Lotos Experience 1995 pp. 34-35\"</ref>\n\n\n\n==Awards==\nFrudakis is a member of the prestigious [[National Sculpture Society]].<ref name=nss_fellow>{{Cite web| author=National Sculpture Society| url=https://nationalsculpture.org/author/zenos_frudakis/| title= Fellows of NSS |accessdate=2012-03-30}}</ref>\n\nIn 1990, Frudakis was invited to participate in Japan's Third Rodin Grand Prize Exhibition, where he won the Hakone Award at Utsukushi-ga-hara Open Air Museum.<ref>Third Rodin Grand Prize Exhibit, The Utsukushi-ga-hara Open Air Museum, Hakone Open Air Museum, Embassies of Greece, Spain, United Kingdom and British Consul, United States, West Germany, 1990, pp. 27-28.</ref> The Museum purchased a cast of Frudakis's sculpture ''Reaching''.<ref>Donald Reynolds, ''Masters of American Sculpture'' (Abbeville Press, 1993), p. 250.</ref>\n\nIn 1991 he was elected into the [[National Academy of Design]] as an Associate member, and became a full Academician in 1993.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"200\">\n<!-- Deleted image removed: Image:Zenos_Frudakis_Dream_To_Fly_Cherry_Hill.jpg|Dream to Fly, Cherry Hill, NJ -->\nImage:Zenos_Frudakis_Gateway_to_Growth_in_progress.JPG|Gateway to Growth (in progress)\nImage:Chef Pep\u00edn, portrait sculpture and sculptor Zenos Frudakis.jpg|Chef Pepin, portrait sculpture and Frudakis\nImage:Zenos_Frudakis_General_Yarborough_Fayetteville.JPG|General Yarborough, Airborne & Special Ops Museum, Fayetteville, NC\nImage:Zenos_Frudakis_Jack_Nicklaus_Louisville.jpg|[[Jack Nicklaus]], Dwight Gahm [[