-new-event-structure/ |publisher=[[Badminton World Federation]] |date=29 November 2017}}</ref> is a series of elite badminton tournaments, sanctioned by [[Badminton World Federation]] (BWF). The BWF World Tour are divided into six levels, namely World Tour Finals, Super 1000, Super 750, Super 500, Super 300 (part of the HSBC World Tour), and the BWF Tour Super 100.<ref>{{cite news |title=Action-Packed Season Ahead! |url=http://bwfworldtour.com/news-single/2018/01/10/action-packed-season-ahead/ |publisher=[[Badminton World Federation]] |date=15 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n''Men's singles''\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 90%;\"\n! Year\n! Tournament\n! Level\n! Opponent\n! Score\n! Result\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | [[2020 Thailand Masters (badminton)#Finals|2020]]\n| align=\"left\" | [[Thailand Masters (badminton)|Thailand Masters]]\n| align=\"left\" | Super 300\n| align=\"left\" | {{flagicon|JPN}} [[Kenta Nishimoto]]\n| align=\"left\" | 16\u201321, 21\u201313, 21\u201312\n| style=\"text-align:left; background:white\" | {{gold1}} '''Winner'''\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | [[2019 Thailand Open (badminton)#Finals|2019]]\n| align=\"left\" | [[Thailand Open (badminton)|Thailand Open]]\n| align=\"left\" | Super 500\n| align=\"left\" | {{flagicon|TPE}} [[Chou Tien-chen]]\n| align=\"left\" | 14\u201321, 21\u201311, 21\u201323\n| style=\"text-align:left; background:white\" | {{silver2}} '''Runner-up'''\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | [[2019 New Zealand Open (badminton)#Finals|2019]] \n| align=\"left\" | [[New Zealand Open (badminton)|New Zealand Open]]\n| align=\"left\" | Super 300 \n| align=\"left\" | {{flagicon|INA}} [[Jonatan Christie]]\n| align=\"left\" | 12\u201321, 13\u201321\n| style=\"text-align:left; background:white\" | {{silver2}} '''Runner-up'''\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | [[2018 German Open (badminton)#Finals|2018]]\n| align=\"left\" | [[German Open (badminton)|German Open]]\n| align=\"left\" | Super 300\n| align=\"left\" | {{flagicon|TPE}} [[Chou Tien-chen]]\n| algin=\"left\" | 19\u201321, 21\u201318, 18\u201321\n| style=\"text-align:left; background:white\" | {{silver2}} '''Runner-up'''\n|}\n\n=== BWF Superseries (1 title) ===\nThe BWF Superseries, launched on 14 December 2006 and implemented in [[2007 in badminton|2007]],<ref>{{cite news|title=BWF Launches Super Series|url=http://www.badminton.org.au/index.php?id=22&tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=136&tx_ttnews%5BbackPid%5D=2&cHash=26fb36d8a5|newspaper=Badminton Australia|date=15 December 2006}}</ref> was a series of elite badminton tournaments, sanctioned by [[Badminton World Federation]] (BWF). BWF Superseries had two level such as [[BWF Superseries|Superseries and Superseries Premier]]. A season of Superseries featured twelve tournaments around the world, which introduced since 2011,<ref>{{cite news|title=Yonex All England Elevated To BWF Premier Super Series Event|url=http://www.ibadmintonstore.com/iBADMINTONstore-News/Yonex-All-England-Elevated-To-BWF-Premier-Super-Se.aspx|accessdate=29 September 2013|newspaper=Badmintonstore.com}}</ref> with successful players invited to the Superseries Finals held at the year end.\n\n''Men's singles''\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n! Year\n! Tournament\n! Opponent\n! Score\n! Result\n|- style=\"background:#FFFFCC\"\n| align=\"center\" | [[2016 Hong Kong Super Series#Finals|2016]]\n| align=\"left\" | [[Hong Kong Open (badminton)|Hong Kong Open]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flagicon|IND}} [[Sameer Verma]]\n| align=\"left\" | 21\u201314, 10\u201321, 21\u201311\n| style=\"text-align:left; background:white\" | {{gold1}} '''Winner'''\n|}\n: {{Color box|#B0C4DE|border=darkgray}} [[BWF Super Series|BWF Superseries Finals]] tournament\n: {{Color box|#DAA520|border=darkgray}} [[BWF Super Series|BWF Superseries Premier]] tournament\n: {{Color box|#FFFFCC|border=darkgray}} [[BWF Superseries]] tournament\n\n=== BWF Grand Prix (2 titles, 2 runners-up) ===\nThe BWF Grand Prix had two level such as [[BWF Grand Prix and Grand Prix Gold|Grand Prix and Grand Prix Gold]]. It is a series of badminton tournaments, sanctioned by [[Badminton World Federation]] (BWF) since 2007.\n\n''Men\u2019s singles''\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n! Year\n! Tournament\n! Opponent\n! Score\n! Result\n|- style=\"background:#FFFF67\"\n| align=\"center\" | [[2017 Malaysia Masters Grand Prix Gold#Finals|2017]]\n| align=\"left\" | [[Malaysia Masters]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flagicon|KOR}} [[Lee Hyun-il]]\n| align=\"left\" | 14\u201321, 21\u201315, 10\u20139 (retired)\n| style=\"text-align:left; background:white\" | {{gold1}} '''Winner'''\n|-\n|- style=\"background:#FFFF67\"\n| align=\"center\" | [[2015 Bitburger Open Grand Prix Gold#Finals|2015]]\n| align=\"left\" | [[Bitburger Open]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flagicon|HKG}} [[Wong Wing Ki]]\n| align=\"left\" | 21\u201312, 21\u201313\n| style=\"text-align:left; background:white\" | {{gold1}} '''Winner'''\n|-\n|- style=\"background:#D4F1C5\"\n| align=\"center\" | [[2015 Canada Open Grand Prix#Finals|2015]]\n| align=\"left\" | [[Canada Open (badminton)|Canada Open]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flagicon|MAS}} [[Lee Chong Wei]]\n| align=\"left\" | 17\u201321, 13\u201321\n| style=\"text-align:left; background:white\" | {{silver2}} '''Runner-up'''\n|-\n|- style=\"background:#D4F1C5\"\n| align=\"center\" | [[2014 Canada Open Grand Prix#Finals|2014]]\n| align=\"left\" | [[Canada Open (badminton)|Canada Open]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flagicon|KOR}} [[Lee Hyun-il]]\n| align=\"left\" | 16\u201321, 14\u201321\n| style=\"text-align:left; background:white\" | {{silver2}} '''Runner-up'''\n|}\n: {{Color box|#FFFF67|border=darkgray}} [[BWF Grand Prix Gold and Grand Prix|BWF Grand Prix Gold]] tournament\n: {{Color box|#D4F1C5|border=darkgray}} [[BWF Grand Prix Gold and Grand Prix|BWF Grand Prix]] tournament\n\n=== BWF International Challenge/Series (4 titles, 2 runners-up) ===\n''Men's singles''\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 90%;\u201d\n! Year\n! 