D5|border=darkgray}} [[BWF International Series]] tournament\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{BWF|B701FB3D-0671-4249-8AAA-758FE92E72C5|NG Ka Long Angus}}\n* {{Sports-Reference}}\n\n{{Top ten badminton players|MS}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ng, Ka Long}}\n[[Category:1994 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong male badminton players]]\n[[Category:Badminton players at the 2016 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic badminton players of Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Badminton players at the 2014 Asian Games]]\n[[Category:Badminton players at the 2018 Asian Games]]\n[[Category:Asian Games competitors for Hong Kong]]\n", "text_old": "{{Chinese name|[[Ng (surname)|Ng]]}}\n{{Infobox badminton player\n| name                    = Angus Ng Ka Long <br /> \u4f0d\u5bb6\u6717\n| image                   = Angus Ng Ka-long.jpg\n| caption                 =\n| nickname                =\n| residence               = [[Hong Kong]]<ref name=bwf>{{cite web|title=NG Ka Long Angus Player Profile|url=http://bwf.tournamentsoftware.com/profile/biography.aspx?id=B701FB3D-0671-4249-8AAA-758FE92E72C5|website=bwf.tournamentsoftware.com|accessdate=26 January 2016}}</ref>\n| birth_name              = \u4f0d\u5bb6\u6717\n| birth_date              = {{birth date and age|df=y|1994|06|24}}<ref name=bwf />\n| birth_place             = [[British Hong Kong|Hong Kong]]<ref name=bwf />\n| death_date              =\n| death_place             =\n| height                  = {{convert|1.81|m|ftin|0|abbr=on}}<ref name=bwf />\n| weight                  = 70 kg\n| country                 = {{HKG}}\n| years_active            =\n| handedness              = Right<ref name=bwf />\n| coach                   =\n| event                   = Men's singles\n| career_record           = 248 wins, 146 losses\n| highest_ranking         = 6\n| date_of_highest_ranking = 23 November 2017<ref name=bwf />\n| current_ranking         = 9\n| date_of_current_ranking = 28 January 2020<ref name=bwf />\n| played                  =\n| medal_templates         =\n{{MedalSport | Men's [[badminton]] }}\n{{MedalCountry | {{HKG}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Badminton Asia Championships#Badminton Asia Team Championships|Asia Mixed Team Championships]] }}\n{{MedalBronze | [[2019 Badminton Asia Mixed Team Championships|2019 Hong Kong]] | Mixed team }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Badminton at the East Asian Games|East Asian Games]] }}\n{{MedalSilver | [[2013 East Asian Games|2013 Tianjin]] | Men's team }}\n{{MedalBronze | [[2013 East Asian Games|2013 Tianjin]] | Men's doubles }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[BWF World Junior Championships|World Junior Championships]] }}\n{{MedalGold | [[2012 BWF World Junior Championships|2012 Chiba]] | [[2012 BWF World Junior Championships \u2013 Boys doubles|Boys' doubles]] }}\n{{MedalBronze | [[2010 BWF World Junior Championships|2010 Guadaljara]] | Boys' doubles }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Badminton Asia Junior Championships|Asian Junior Championships]] }}\n{{MedalBronze | [[2012 Asian Junior Badminton Championships|2012 Gimcheon]] | Boys' doubles }}\n{{MedalBronze | [[2008 Asian Junior Badminton Championships|2008 Kuala Lumpur]] | Mixed team }}\n| bwf_id                  = B701FB3D-0671-4249-8AAA-758FE92E72C5\n}}\n{{Chinese|title=Ng Ka Long|s=\u4f0d\u5bb6\u6717|t=\u4f0d\u5bb6\u6717|p=W\u01d4 Ji\u0101l\u01ceng|w=Wu Chia Lang|j=Ng5 Gaa1 Long5}}\n\n'''Angus Ng Ka Long''' (born 24 June 1994) is a [[badminton]] player from [[Hong Kong]]. He has a career-high ranking of 6 in men's singles, and has beaten other top 10 players like [[Lin Dan]], [[Lee Chong Wei]], [[Chen Long]], [[Chou Tien-chen]], [[Jan \u00d8. J\u00f8rgensen]], and [[Son Wan-ho]].\n\n== Early life and education ==\nNg trained at the [[Hong Kong Sports Institute]]. According to him, his father is the main influence to his career.<ref name=bwf />\n\n== Career ==\nAt the [[2010 BWF World Junior Championships]], [[Guadalajara]] he won a bronze medal in the men's doubles. He won gold in the men's doubles in [[2012 BWF World Junior Championships|2012]] in Chiba Prefecture. He won bronze in the [[2012 Asian Junior Badminton Championships|2012 Asian Junior Championships]] men's doubles.\n\nIn 2013, Ng participated in the [[2013 BWF World Championships]] in [[Guangzhou]], China, was the runner-up at the [[Vietnam International|Vietnam International Challenge]] in men's singles, and competed in the [[2013 East Asian Games]] in [[Tianjin]] for Hong Kong, winning a silver medal in the men's singles and bronze in the men's doubles.\n\nIn 2014, Ng won the [[China International (badminton)|China International Challenge]], [[Osaka International (badminton)|Osaka International Challenge]] and [[Irish Open (badminton)|Irish Open]]. He was the runner-up at the [[Canadian Open (badminton)|Canadian Grand Prix]] and the [[Swiss International (badminton)|Swiss International]] tournaments.\n\nIn 2015, Ng won the men's singles at the [[Austrian International|Austrian Open]]. He later won his first Grand Prix title at the [[2015 Bitburger Open Grand Prix Gold|Bitburger Open]]. <ref>{{cite web|last1=Vandervorst |first1=Elm |title=BITBURGER OPEN Finals \u2013 Ka Long way to go |url=http://www.badzine.net/news/bitburger-open-finals-%E2%80%93-a-long-way-to-go/36080/ |website=badzine.net |accessdate=30 January 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160204105205/http://www.badzine.net/news/bitburger-open-finals-%E2%80%93-a-long-way-to-go/36080/ |archivedate=4 February 2016 }}</ref> He also came second at the Canadian Grand Prix and reached the semifinals at the [[2015 Hong Kong Super Series|Hong Kong Super Series]], having beaten top 10 players like [[Lin Dan]] and [[Chou Tien-chen|Chou Tien Chen]] before losing to the legendary [[Lee Chong Wei]].\n\nIn 2016, Ng made history by becoming the first home player to win the men's singles title at the Hong Kong Open, beating India's [[Sameer Verma]] in the final.\n\n== Achievements ==\n\n=== East Asian Games ===\n''Men's doubles''\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 90%;\"\n! Year\n! Venue\n! Partner\n! Opponent\n! Score\n! Result\n|- style=\"background:#FFAAAA\"\n| align=\"center\" | 2013\n| align=\"left\" | Binhai New Area Dagang Gymnasium,<br />[[Tianjin, China]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flagicon|HKG}} [[Lee Chun Hei]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flagicon|TPE}} [[Lee Sheng-mu]] <br /> {{flagicon|TPE}} [[Tsai Chia-hsin]]\n| align=\"left\" | 11\u201321, 19\u201321\n| style=\"text-align:left; background:white\" | [[File:Med 3.png|Bronze]] '''Bronze'''\n|}\n\n=== BWF World Junior Championships ===\n''Boys' doubles''\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 90%;\"\n! Year\n! Venue\n! Partner\n! Opponent\n! Score\n! Result\n|- style=\"background:#98FB98\"\n| align=\"center\" | [[2012 BWF World Junior Championships \u2013 Boys doubles|2012]]\n| align=\"left\" | [[Chiba Port Arena]],<br />[[Chiba, Chiba|Chiba, Japan]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flagicon|HKG}} [[Lee Chun Hei]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flagicon|JPN}} [[Takuto Inoue]] <br /> {{flagicon|JPN}} [[Yuki Kaneko (badminton)|Yuki Kaneko]]\n| align=\"left\" | 21\u201316, 21\u201317\n| style=\"text-align:left; background:white\" | [[File:Med 1.png|Gold]] '''Gold'''\n|-\n|- style=\"background:#98FB98\"\n| align=\"center\" | [[2010 BWF World Junior Championships#Finals 3|2010]]\n| align=\"left\" | Domo del Code Jalisco,<br />[[Guadalajara, Mexico]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flagicon|HKG}} [[Lee Chun Hei]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flagicon|MAS}} [[Nelson Heg Wei Keat]] <br /> {{flagicon|MAS}} [[Teo Ee Yi]]\n| align=\"left\" | 21\u201317, 15\u201321, 11\u201321\n| style=\"text-align:left; background:white\" | [[File:Med 3.png|Bronze]] '''Bronze'''\n|}\n\n=== Asian Junior Championships ===\n''Boys' doubles''\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 90%;\"\n! Year\n! Venue\n! Partner\n! Opponent\n! Score\n! Result\n|- style=\"background:#AABBCC\"\n| align=\"center\" | [[2012 Asian Junior Badminton Championships|2012]]\n| align=\"left\" | Gimcheon Indoor Stadium,<br />[[Gimcheon]], [[South Korea]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flagicon|HKG}} [[Lee Chun Hei]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flagicon|INA}} [[Arya Maulana Aldiartama]] <br /> {{flagicon|INA}} [[Edi Subaktiar]]\n| align=\"left\" | 21\u201315, 24\u201326, 15\u201321\n| style=\"text-align:left; background:white\" | [[File:Med 3.png|Bronze]] '''Bronze'''\n|}\n\n=== BWF World Tour (1 title, 3 runners-up) ===\nThe BWF World Tour, announced on 19 March 2017 and implemented in 2018,<ref>{{cite news |title=BWF Launches New Events Structure |url=http://bwfbadminton.com/news-single/2017/03/19/bwf-launches-new-event-structure/ |publisher=[[Badminton World Federation]] |date=29 November 2017}}</ref> is a series of elite badminton tournaments, sanctioned by [[Badminton World Federation]] (BWF). The BWF World Tour are divided into six levels, namely World Tour Finals, Super 1000, Super 750, Super 500, Super 300 (part of the HSBC World Tour), and the BWF Tour Super 100.<ref>{{cite news |title=Action-Packed Season Ahead! |url=http://bwfworldtour.com/news-single/2018/01/10/action-packed-season-ahead/ |publisher=[[Badminton World Federation]] |date=15 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n''Men's singles''\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 90%;\"\n! Year\n! Tournament\n! Level\n! Opponent\n! Score\n! Result\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | [[2020 Thailand Masters (badminton)#Finals|2020]]\n| align=\"left\" | [[Thailand Masters (badminton)|Thailand Masters]]\n| align=\"left\" | Super 300\n| align=\"left\" | {{flagicon|JPN}} [[Kenta Nishimoto]]\n| align=\"left\" | 16\u201321, 21\u201313, 21\u201312\n| style=\"text-align:left; background:white\" | {{gold1}} '''Winner'''\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | [[2019 Thailand Open (badminton)#Finals|2019]]\n| align=\"left\" | [[Thailand Open (badminton)|Thailand Open]]\n| align=\"left\" | Super 500\n| align=\"left\" | {{flagicon|TPE}} [[Chou Tien-chen]]\n| align=\"left\" | 14\u201321, 21\u201311, 21\u201323\n| style=\"text-align:left; background:white\" | {{silver2}} '''Runner-up'''\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | [[2019 New Zealand Open (badminton)#Finals|2019]] \n| align=\"left\" | [[New Zealand Open (badminton)|New Zealand Open]]\n| align=\"left\" | Super 300 \n| align=\"left\" | {{flagicon|INA}} [[Jonatan Christie]]\n| align=\"left\" | 12\u201321, 13\u201321\n| style=\"text-align:left; background:white\" | {{silver2}} '''Runner-up'''\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | [[2018 German Open (badminton)#Finals|2018]]\n| align=\"left\" | [[German Open (badminton)|German Open]]\n| align=\"left\" | Super 300\n| align=\"left\" | {{flagicon|TPE}} [[Chou Tien-chen]]\n| algin=\"left\" | 19\u201321, 21\u201318, 18\u201321\n| style=\"text-align:left; background:white\" | {{silver2}} '''Runner-up'''\n|}\n\n=== BWF Superseries (1 title) ===\nThe BWF Superseries, launched on 14 December 2006 and implemented in [[2007 in badminton|2007]],<ref>{{cite news|title=BWF Launches Super Series|url=http://www.badminton.org.au/index.php?id=22&tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=136&tx_ttnews%5BbackPid%5D=2&cHash=26fb36d8a5|newspaper=Badminton Australia|date=15 December 2006}}</ref> was a series of elite badminton tournaments, sanctioned by [[Badminton World Federation]] (BWF). BWF Superseries had two level such as [[BWF Superseries|Superseries and Superseries Premier]]. A season of Superseries featured twelve tournaments around the world, which introduced since 2011,<ref>{{cite news|title=Yonex All England Elevated To BWF Premier Super Series Event|url=http://www.ibadmintonstore.com/iBADMINTONstore-News/Yonex-All-England-Elevated-To-BWF-Premier-Super-Se.aspx|accessdate=29 September 2013|newspaper=Badmintonstore.com}}</ref> with successful players invited to the Superseries Finals held at the year end.\n\n''Men's singles''\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n! Year\n! Tournament\n! Opponent\n! Score\n! Result\n|- style=\"background:#FFFFCC\"\n| align=\"center\" | [[2016 Hong Kong Super Series#